{"title_page": "Ansar al-Islam", "text_new": "{{Hatnote|Not to be confused with [[Jabhat Ansar al-Islam]].}}\n{{Infobox War Faction\n|name=Ansar al-Islam\n|native_name = \u062c\u0645\u0627\u0639\u0629 \u0623\u0646\u0635\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\n|native_name_lang = Ar\n|war = the [[Iraq War]], [[Iraqi insurgency (post-U.S. withdrawal)|Iraqi insurgency]], [[Syrian Civil War]], and the [[War on Terror|Global War on Terrorism]]\n|image = [[File:Flag of Ansar al-Islam.svg|border|200px]]\n|caption = The Flag of Ansar al-Islam \u2013 al Sahab<ref name=lwjjan2012 />\n|active = September 2001 \u2013 29 August 2014 <small>(main faction)</small><br />\n29 August 2014\u2013''present'' <small>(independent pro-AQ Iraqi and Syrian factions)</small><ref name=\"al-monitor.com\">{{cite web|title=IS disciplines some emirs to avoid losing base|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/security/2014/09/is-takfiri-caliphate.html#|date=2 September 2014|accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"israelnationalnews.com\">{{cite web|title=Iraqi Jihadist Group Swears Alleigance to Islamic State|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/184544#.VAxa5xagSSk|date=29 August 2014|accessdate= 2 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"broken\">{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2016/08/jihadists-and-other-rebels-claim-to-have-broken-through-siege-of-aleppo.php|title=Jihadists and other rebels claim to have broken through siege of Aleppo|author=Thomas Joscelyn|work=The Long War Journal|date=7 August 2016|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"new name\" />\n|ideology = [[Salafism]]\n*[[Salafist Jihadism]]\n*[[Wahhabism]]<ref name=hrwa>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/backgrounder/mena/ansarbk020503.htm|title=Ansar al-Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan|work=[[Human Rights Watch]]}}</ref>\n|leaders = [[Mullah Krekar]] <small>(2001\u201303)</small><br />[[Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i]]{{POW}} <small>(2003\u201310)</small><br />[[Abu Hashim al-Ibrahim]] <small>(2010\u201314)</small><ref name=lwjjan2012 />\n|headquarters = [[Hamrin Mountains]]<ref name=\"new name\">{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1208661/middle-east#.WjGjatHn6gc.twitter |title=Kurdish militant group re-emerges in northern Iraq under new name |author=Suadad al-Salhy |work=Arab News |date=14 December 2017 |accessdate=14 December 2017 }}</ref>\n|area = [[Iraqi Kurdistan]],<ref name=hrwa /> [[Iraq]], [[Syria]]\n|strength = Before split: 350+<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/Documents/opeds/4224e31e5fa37.pdf|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref><br />2017: Hundreds <small>(acc. to Iraqi officials)</small><ref name=\"new name\" />\n|clans = [[White Flags]] <small>(Iraqi gov. claim)</small><ref name=\"new name\" />\n|partof = [[Rouse the Believers Operations Room]]<ref name=\"joint room\">{{cite web|url=http://nedaa-sy.com/en/news/9078|title=Military groups calling themselves \"the finest factions of the Levant\" form joint operations room|publisher=Syria Call|date=15 October 2018|accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n|previous = Jund al-Islam\n|became = {{flag|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}} <small>(main faction)</small><ref name=\"isis\" /><br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban (original).svg|border}} [[White Flags]] <small>(Splinter faction, Iraqi government claim, since 2017)</small>\n|allies = {{flag|al-Qaeda}}<ref name=\"iraqiupdate\">{{cite web|title=Key Updates on Iraq's Sunni Insurgent Groups|url=http://brown-moses.blogspot.co.uk/2014/05/key-updates-on-iraqs-sunni-insurgent.html|author=Aymenn Jawad Al-Tamimi|publisher=Brown Moses Blog|date=11 May 2014|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref><br>{{flagdeco|ISIL}} [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]<ref>https://www.pri.org/stories/2014-07-21/youve-heard-about-isis-you-havent-heard-about-these-guys</ref><br/>{{flagicon image|Flag of Hayat Tahrir al-Sham.svg}} [[Tahrir al-Sham]]<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of Turkistan Islamic Party.svg}} [[Turkistan Islamic Party]]<br>{{flagicon image|Infobox Ajnad al-Kavkaz flag.png}} [[Ajnad al-Kavkaz]]<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of the Kurdistan Islamic Group.svg}} [[Kurdistan Islamic Group]]<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of the Islamic Front (Syria) (Black).svg}} [[Islamic Front (Syria)|Islamic Front]] <small>(2013\u20132015)</small><br>[[Guardians of Religion Organization]]<br>{{flagicon image|Emblem of the Ansar al-Deen Front.svg}} [[Ansar al-Din Front]]\n<br>{{flagdeco|Syrian Opposition}} [[Free Syrian Army]]<br>{{flag|Iran}} <small>(allegedly)</small><ref>https://jamestown.org/program/the-hidden-hand-of-iran-in-the-resurgence-of-ansar-al-islam/</ref>\n|opponents = \n{{flagdeco|Kurdistan}} [[Peshmerga]]<br>{{IRQ}}<br>{{SYR}}<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of Syrian Democratic Forces.svg}} [[Syrian Democratic Forces]]<br>{{USA}}<br>{{flag|Iran}}<br>{{flagicon image|InfoboxHez.PNG}} [[Hezbollah]]<br>{{flag|Russia}}\n|battles = [[Iraq War]]\n*[[Kurdistan Islamist conflict]]\n[[Syrian Civil War]]\n*[[Battle of Aleppo (2012\u20132016)]]\n**[[2016 Aleppo summer campaign]]\n*[[2018 Idlib demilitarization]]<ref name=\"joint room\" />\n*[[Northwestern Syria offensive (April 2019\u2013present)]]\n[[Iraqi Civil War (2014\u20132017)]]\n}}\n\n'''Ansar al-Islam''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0646\u0635\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645}} ''{{transl|ar|An\u1e63\u0101r al-Isl\u0101m}}'') or '''Ansar al-Islam fi Kurdistan''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0646\u0635\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u064a \u0643\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646}} ''{{transl|ar|An\u1e63\u0101r al-Isl\u0101m f\u012b Kurdist\u0101n}}''),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/backgrounder/mena/ansarbk020503.htm|title=Ansar al-Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan (Human Rights Watch Backgrounder, )}}</ref> also referred to as '''AAI''',<ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\">Chalk, Peter, ''Encyclopedia of Terrorism'' Volume 1, 2012, ABC-CLIO</ref> is a [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] [[Muslim]] [[insurgent]] group in Iraq<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fas.org/irp/world/para/ansar.htm |title=Ansar al-Islam |publisher=Federation of American Scientists |date= |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> and Syria.<ref name=iraqiupdate /> It was established in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]] by former al-Qaeda members in 2001 as a [[Salafist]] [[Islamist]] movement that imposed a strict application of [[Sharia]] in villages it controlled around Biyara to the northeast of [[Halabja]], near the Iranian border. Its ideology follows a [[Athari|literal]] interpretation of the Koran and promotes a return to what it claims is the example of the first Muslims ([[Salaf]]).<ref>[http://atimes.com/atimes/Middle_East/FA09Ak02.html ''Asia Times'': \"Ansar al-Islam refuses to lie down\" by Valentinas Mite] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208224138/http://atimes.com/atimes/Middle_East/FA09Ak02.html |date=2015-12-08 }} January 9, 2004</ref> Following the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], the group became an insurgent group which fought against the Kurdish government, [[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq|American led forces]] and their Iraqi allies. The group continued to fight the Iraqi Government following the [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq (2007\u20132011)|withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq]], and sent members to Syria to fight the Government following the outbreak of the [[Syrian Civil War]].\n\nThe group was a [[List of designated terrorist organizations|designated terrorist organization]]<!-- see link for inclusion of national bodies --> in the United Nations, Australia, Canada, Israel, the United Kingdom and the United States, and a known affiliate of the [[al-Qaeda]] network.<ref>Schanzer, Jonathan. ''Al-Qaeda's armies: Middle East affiliate groups & the next generation of terror''. Specialist Press International. New York, 2005.</ref>\n\nOn 29 August 2014, a statement on the behalf of 50 leaders and members of Ansar al-Islam announced that the group was merging with the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]], thereby officially dissolving the organization.<ref name=\"isis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/security/2014/09/is-takfiri-caliphate.html#|title=IS disciplines some emirs to avoid losing base \u2013 Al-Monitor: the Pulse of the Middle East|work=Al-Monitor|date=2014-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\"isis1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/184544#.VAxa5xagSSk|title=Jihadist Group Swears Loyalty to Islamic State \u2013 Middle East \u2013 News \u2013 Arutz Sheva|work=Arutz Sheva|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref> However, some small elements within Ansar al-Islam rejected this merger, and continued to function as an independent organization.<ref name=\"isis\" /> When a previously unknown Kurdish militant [[White Flags|group using white flags]] appeared in Iraq in 2017, Iraqi security and intelligence officials argued that this was a [[front organization]] of Ansar al-Islam, which reportedly still had hundreds of fighters operating in the [[Hamrin Mountains]].<ref name=\"new name\" />\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation===\nAnsar al-Islam was formed in September 2001 from a merger of Jund al-Islam (Soldiers of Islam), led by [[Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i]], and a splinter group from the [[Kurdistan Islamic Movement]] led by [[Mullah Krekar]]. Krekar became the leader of the merged Ansar al-Islam, which opposed an agreement made between IMK and the dominant Kurdish group in the area, [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] (PUK). The group later made an allegiance to al-Qaeda and allegedly received direct funds from the terror network.<ref>''Terrorism & Its Effects''. Sanchez, Juan. Global Media, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe two IMK splinter groups that formed Jund al Islam on 1 September 2001, had some early battlefield successes in the same month when it killed 42 PUK fighters in an ambush, which led to them drawing in more IMK leaders their ranks, on 10 December 2001, the group became known as AAI (Ansar al-Islam ).<ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\" />\n\nAnsar al-Islam initially comprised approximately 300 men, many of them veterans of the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]], and a proportion being neither Kurd nor Arab. During its stay in the Biyara region near the Iranian border, there were allegations of logistical support from \"powerful factions in Iran\".<ref name=\"crisisgroup\">{{cite web |url=http://www.crisisgroup.org/en/regions/middle-east-north-africa/iraq-iran-gulf/iraq/B004-radical-islam-in-iraqi-kurdistan-the-mouse-that-roared.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111121202552/http://www.crisisgroup.org/en/regions/middle-east-north-africa/iraq-iran-gulf/iraq/B004-radical-islam-in-iraqi-kurdistan-the-mouse-that-roared.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-11-21 |title=Radical Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan: The Mouse that Roared?|publisher=International Crisis Group |date=2014-02-07 |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n\nThe roots of Ansar al-Islam can be traced to the mid-1990s. The group consists of various Islamist factions that splintered from the Islamic Movement of Kurdistan (IMK). In 2001, shortly before the 9/11 attacks, leaders of several Kurdish Islamist factions visited the al-Qa'ida leadership in Afghanistan planning to create a base for al-Qa'ida in northern Iraq. A document found in Kabul stated the groups' objectives, which was to \"\"expel those Jews and Christians from Kurdistan and join the way of jihad, [and] rule every piece of land \u2026 with the Islamic Shari'a rule.\" This was also confirmed by the ''Los Angeles Times'', based upon interviews with an Ansar prisoner, which stated that in October 2000, Kurdish Islamist leaders sent jihadists to bin Laden's camps. They received the message from bin Laden that Kurdish Islamic cells should unite.<ref>[http://www.meforum.org/579/ansar-al-islam-back-in-iraq Ansar al-Islam: Back in Iraq :: Middle East Quarterly<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Period up to the Iraq War===\nUpon its founding, Ansar al-Islam declared war on all secular political parties in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]], throughout 2002, AAI carried out attacks and targeting killings of these Kurdish groups, particularly high-level PUK members, as well as engaging in battles and skirmishes with the PUK. The attacks allowed the AAI to carve out space to impose its form of Islamist governance in northeast Iraq under its spiritual founder and leader [[Mullah Krekar]]. [[Sharia Law]] was implemented, enforcing it through bombing of businesses it deemed in-Islamic, acid attacks on women it deemed immodest and beheading of those it deemed apostates.<ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\" />\n\nVillagers under Ansar al-Islam's control were subjected to harsh sharia laws; musical instruments were destroyed and singing forbidden. The only school for girls in the area was destroyed, and all pictures of women removed from merchandise labels. Sufi shrines were desecrated and members of the Kaka'i (a religious group also known as [[Ahl-e Haqq]]) were forced to convert to Islam or flee. Former prisoners of the group also claim that Ansar al-Islam routinely used torture and severe beatings when interrogating prisoners. Beheading of prisoners had also been reported.<ref name=\"hrw\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/backgrounder/mena/ansarbk020503.htm |title=Ansar al-Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date= |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2001 and early 2002, the AAI received an inflow of foreign (mostly Arab) jihadists fleeing Afghanistan following the [[United States invasion of Afghanistan|2001 invasion of Afghanistan]], including [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]].<ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\" />\n\nPrior to the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|US 2003 invasion of Iraq]], Paramilitary teams from the [[Special Activities Division]] (SAD) and the Army's [[10th Special Forces Group (United States)|10th Special Forces Group]] entered Iraq and cooperated with [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] [[Peshmerga]] to attack Ansar al-Islam. Together they launched [[Operation Viking Hammer]] in March 2003 which dealt a huge blow to the terrorist group which resulted in the deaths of a substantial number of terrorists and the uncovering of a [[Chemical warfare|chemical weapons]] facility at Sargat.<ref>''Plan of Attack'', [[Bob Woodward]], Simon and Schuster, 2004.</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/ccbc37f1-3955-4a19-a72d-a7c210a6a036 |title = Pentagon: US in Syria 'for the long haul;' hails Peshmerga in 'Operation Viking Hammer'}}</ref> Sargat was the only facility of its type discovered in Iraq.<ref>{{cite book |title=Operation Hotel California: The Clandestine War inside Iraq |first=Mike |last=Tucker |author2=Charles Faddis |year=2008 |publisher=The Lyons Press |isbn=978-1-59921-366-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/operationhotelca00tuck }}</ref><ref>[http://wamu.org/audio/dr/08/10/r2081007-22101.asx An interview on public radio with the author] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930081326/http://wamu.org/audio/dr/08/10/r2081007-22101.asx |date=September 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\" />\n\n===Iraq War===\n{{further|Ansar al-Sunna}}\nIn September 2003, members of Ansar al-Islam who had fled to [[Iran]] after the 2003 joint operation by Iraqi and US forces against them announced the creation of a group called [[Jamaat Ansar al-Sunna]], which was dedicated to expelling U.S. occupation forces from Iraq. Ansar al-Sunna became a prominent insurgent group active in the so-called [[Sunni Triangle]], carrying out kidnappings, suicide bombings, and guerilla attacks.\n\nIn November or December 2007 the [[Ansar al-Sunna]] group formally acknowledged being derived from Ansar al-Islam, and reverted to using that name.<ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://counterterrorismblog.org/2007/12/ansar_alsunnah_acknowledges_re.php |archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091013162709/http://counterterrorismblog.org/2007/12/ansar_alsunnah_acknowledges_re.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-10-13 |title=Ansar al-Sunnah Acknowledges Relationship with Ansar al-Islam, Reverts to Using Ansar al-Islam Name |publisher=Counterterrorism Blog |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref>\n\n===Iraqi Insurgency (post-U.S. withdrawal)===\nAnsar al-Islam remained active after the [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq (2007\u20132011)|withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq]] of 2011, taking part in the [[Iraqi insurgency (post-U.S. withdrawal)|insurgency]] against Iraq's central government. Attacks against Iraqi security forces have been claimed by the group, particularly around [[Mosul]] and [[Kirkuk]].<ref name=iraqiupdate />\n\n===Syrian Civil War===\nAnsar al-Islam has established a presence in Syria to take part in the [[Syrian Civil War]], initially under the name of \"Ansar al-Sham\",<ref>{{cite web|title=Musings of an Iraqi Brasenostril on Jihad: Comprehensive Reference Guide to Sunni Militant Groups in Iraq|url=http://jihadology.net/2014/01/23/musings-of-an-iraqi-brasenostril-on-jihad-comprehensive-reference-guide-to-sunni-militant-groups-in-iraq/|author=Aymenn Jawad Al-Tamimi|publisher=Jihadology.net|date=23 January 2014|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> later under its own name. The group coordinated with the [[Ahfad al-Rasul Brigades]] to bomb [[Syrian Armed Forces|Syrian military]] compounds in [[Damascus]] in August 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-crisis-explosion/bomb-explosion-hits-security-area-of-damascus-activists-idUSBRE89A1CB20121011|title=Bomb explosion hits security area of Damascus: activists|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|date=12 October 2012}}</ref> It also played a role in the [[Battle of Aleppo (2012\u2013present)|Battle of Aleppo]] and coordinates with other Salafist groups including al-Qaeda's [[al-Nusra Front]] and the [[Islamic Front (Syria)|Islamic Front]].<ref name=\"iraqiupdate\" /> The Syrian Ansar al-Islam units in Aleppo remained independent when the main faction joined ISIL in 2014.<ref name=\"complete history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aymennjawad.org/2015/12/a-complete-history-of-jamaat-ansar-al-islam |title=A Complete History of Jamaat Ansar al-Islam}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, they fought alongside the al-Nusra Front during a [[Aleppo offensive (June\u2013August 2016)|major offensive]] in the city.<ref name=\"broken\" /> A military commander of the group, Abu Layth al-Tunisi, was reportedly killed in combat during this operation, probably southwest of Aleppo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/top-salafist-commander-killed-southern-aleppo/|title=Top salafist commander killed in southern Aleppo|first=Zen|last=Adra|work=[[Al-Masdar News]]|date=20 August 2016|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://syrianperspective.com/2016/08/terrorist-numbers-drying-up-in-aleppo-as-syrian-army-kills-over-60-syrian-army-slashes-rodents-in-hama-major-advance-in-daarayyaa-snafu-at-idlib-crossing.html#dblFlZYx1pGMCUG5.99 |title=Terrorist Numbers Drying Up In Aleppo as Syrian Army Kills Over 60|date=2016-08-20}}</ref> By July 2018, the Syrian faction of Ansar al-Islam (not to be confused with the Syrian [[Ansar al-Sham]] group, which fought in the same area) was active in [[Latakia Governorate]], raiding local Syrian Army outposts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2018/07/ansar-al-islam-raids-assad-regime-position-in-latakia.php |title=Ansar al-Islam raids Assad regime position in Latakia |author=Thomas Joscelyn |work=[[Long War Journal]] |date=11 July 2018 |accessdate=14 July 2018 }}</ref> Following the Turkish-Russian agreement to [[2018 Idlib demilitarization|demilitarize Idlib]] in September 2018, the Syrian branch of Ansar al-Islam joined the [[Rouse the Believers Operations Room]] with other al-Qaeda-linked groups to oppose any attempts to carry out the demilitarization of northwestern Syria.<ref name=\"joint room\" />\n\n===Reported re-emergence in Iraq===\n{{further|White Flags}}\nAfter the defeat of ISIL and the capture of [[Tuz Khurmatu]] by Turkmen and Shiite [[Popular Mobilization Forces]] during the [[2017 Iraqi\u2013Kurdish conflict]], the town and its surroundings came under almost daily rocket attacks by a militant faction that used a white flag with the black head of a lion. These \"[[White Flags]]\", led by Assi Al-Qawali, reportedly consisted of Kurdish militants, ex-ISIL fighters and [[Kurdistan Democratic Party]] supporters who claimed to be fighting to \"liberate the Kurdish lands\u2014occupied by the Iranian Shiite militias\". Iraqi security and intelligence officials said that intelligence reports made it likely that this new group was a [[front organization]] of Ansar al-Islam, which reportedly still had hundreds of fighters operating in the [[Hamrin Mountains]].<ref name=\"new name\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebaghdadpost.com/en/story/22911/Iraqi-security-forces-repel-White-Flags-terrorists-in-Tuz-Khurmatu |title=Iraqi security forces repel White Flags terrorists in Tuz Khurmatu |author= |work=[[The Baghdad Post]] |date=25 January 2018 |accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October 2019, Ansar al-Islam claimed responsibility for an IED attack on a [[Popular Mobilization Forces]] vehicle in the [[Diyala Governorate]] in northeastern Iraq.<ref>https://jihadology.net/2019/10/30/new-statement-from-an%e1%b9%a3ar-al-islam-attack-in-iraq/</ref>\n\n==Alleged ties to Saddam Hussein's regime==\nIn a \"Special Analysis\" report dated July 31, 2002, the U.S. [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] (DIA) concluded the following regarding possible connections between Saddam's regime and Ansar al-Islam:\n\"The Iraqi regime seeks to influence and manipulate political events in the Kurdish-controlled north and probably has some type of assets in contact with Ansar al-Islam, either through liaison or through penetration by an intelligence asset.\"<ref name=DIAjul2002>DIA, Special Analysis, July 31, 2002, cited in [http://intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf Postwar Findings about Iraq's WMD Programs and Links to Terrorism and How they Compare with Prewar Assessments, pg. 71.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060921074629/http://intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf |date=September 21, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2003, the U.S. alleged that Ansar al-Islam provided a possible link between [[Saddam Hussein]] and al-Qaeda, and said to prepare to unveil new evidence of it.<ref name=Bbc31-1-3 />\nAnsar's leader [[Mullah Krekar]] in January 2003 denied links of Ansar with Saddam Hussein's government.<ref name=Bbc31-1-3 /> U.S. terrorism expert [[Rohan Gunaratna]] in January 2003 agreed with Krekar that links of Ansar with Iraqi Government were never proven.<ref name=Bbc31-1-3 />\n\nIn February 2003, then [[United States Secretary of State]] [[Colin Powell]] told the [[United Nations Security Council]], \"Baghdad has an agent in the most senior levels of the radical organization, Ansar al-Islam, that controls this corner of Iraq. In 2000 this agent offered Al Qaida safe haven in the region. After we swept Al Qaida from Afghanistan, some of its members accepted this safe haven.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2003/02/20030205-1.html | title=U.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell Addresses the U.N. Security Council | date=2003-02-05}}</ref>\n\nIn March\u2013April 2003, the BBC reported that a captured Iraqi intelligence officer had indicated that a senior Ansar leader, Abu Wail, was an Iraqi intelligence officer.<ref name=Canadian /> If that was true, then Saddam's regime had some influence on Ansar, said the BBC.<ref name=Canadian />\nSaddam's interest could have been to have Ansar as a force directly opposing Kurdish independence in northern Iraq, said the BBC.<ref name=Canadian />\n\nIn January 2004, Powell acknowledged that his speech of February 2003 presented no hard evidence of collaboration between Saddam and al-Qaeda; he told reporters at a State Department press conference that \"I have not seen smoking gun, concrete evidence about the connection, but I do believe the connections existed.\"<ref>NBC, MSNBC, AP, \"[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/ID/3909150/ No proof links Iraq, al-Qaeda, Powell says],\" MSNBC News Services (8 January 2004).</ref>\n\nThe [[Senate Report on Pre-war Intelligence on Iraq]], issued in 2004, concluded that Saddam \"was aware of Ansar al-Islam and [[al-Qaeda]] presence in northeastern Iraq, but the groups' presence was considered a threat to the regime and the Iraqi government attempted intelligence collection operations against them. The [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] (DIA) stated that information from senior Ansar al-Islam detainees revealed that the group viewed Saddam's regime as apostate, and denied any relationship with it.\"<ref>[http://intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf Senate Intelligence Committee Report p.92-93.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060921074629/http://intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf |date=September 21, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. [[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence|Select Committee on Intelligence]] in September 2006 again stated that: 'Postwar information reveals that Baghdad viewed Ansar al-Islam as a threat to the regime and (...) attempted to collect intelligence on the group'.<ref name=\"Conclusions\">{{cite news|title=Senate Select Committee on Intelligence on Postwar Findings About Iraq's WMD Programs and Links to Terrorism and How They Compare with Prewar Assessments. 109th Congress, 2nd Session |url=http://www.intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf |accessdate=8 February 2015 |publisher=[[Senate Report on Pre-war Intelligence on Iraq]] |date=8 September 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215060854/http://www.intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf |archivedate=February 15, 2015 }}(See III.G, Conclusions 5 and 6, p.109.)</ref>\n\nAfter Powell had left office, he in 2008 acknowledged that he was skeptical of the evidence presented to him for the speech of February 2003. In an interview, he told [[Barbara Walters]] then that he considered that speech a \"blot\" on his record and that he felt \"terrible\" about assertions that he made in the speech that turned out to be false. He said, \"There were some people in the intelligence community who knew at that time that some of these sources were not good, and shouldn't be relied upon, and they didn't speak up. That devastated me.\" When asked specifically about a Saddam/al-Qaeda connection, Powell responded, \"I have never seen a connection. \u2026 I can't think otherwise because I'd never seen evidence to suggest there was one.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=ABC News: Colin Powell on Iraq, Race, and Hurricane Relief|url=http://abcnews.go.com/2020/Politics/story?id=1105979&page=1|publisher=ABC News|date=2008-09-08|accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==Swedish fund-raising case==\nAli Berzengi and Ferman Abdullah, the owner of a [[falafel]] stand in [[Stockholm]], raised money for what they claimed was poor children and Muslims. The money was then transferred through Abdulla's food stand, using the [[hawala]] transfer system.<ref name=sydsvenskan>{{cite news|author=L\u00f6nnaeus, Olle, Orrenius, Niklas, Magnusson, Erik |title=Kiosken var en terrorbank |url=http://sydsvenskan.se/sverige/article141850.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060215223827/http://sydsvenskan.se/sverige/article141850.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-02-15 |newspaper=[[Sydsvenskan]] |date=2006-02-12 |accessdate=2007-01-24 |language=sv}}</ref> The [[Swedish Security Service]] was informed in 2002 that people in Sweden had transferred money to Ansar al-Islam.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Swedish Security Service 2005|publisher=[[Swedish Security Service]]|year=2005|url=http://www.sakerhetspolisen.se/Publikationer/swedish_security_service_2005.pdf|accessdate=2007-01-22}} {{dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> On April 19, 2004, Berzengi and Abdulla were arrested along with another Iraqi, Shaho Shahab, and [[Lebanon|Lebanese]]-born Bilal Ramadan. Ramadan was released in September after a court found that there wasn't enough evidence to keep him in custody. Shahab was released in December after the government decided to deport him to Iraq. However, since Shahab risks receiving the death penalty in his home country, the deportation has not been carried out.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Iraqis charged in Sweden with transferring money to al-Zarqawi|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2005-04-05-alzarqawi-money_x.htm|publisher=[[USA Today]]/[[Associated Press]]|date=2005-05-04|accessdate=2007-01-22}}</ref> In Abdulla's apartment the police found a letter from a man who claimed to have been in contact with [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]], the leader of [[al-Qaeda in Iraq]], as well as a detailed manual on how to use coded language.<ref name=sydsvenskan />\n\nOn May 12, 2005, Abdulla and Berzengi were convicted by the Stockholm District Court for \"planning of terrorist offences\" ({{lang-sv|f\u00f6rberedelse till terroristbrott}}) and \"planning of public devastation\" ({{lang-sv|f\u00f6rberedelse till allm\u00e4nfarlig \u00f6del\u00e4ggelse}}) according to [[Swedish law]]. Accord to the court they had transferred approximately one million [[Swedish krona|SEK]] to Ansar al-Islam. According to the court there was strong evidence that the collected money had the specific purpose of financing terrorist attacks. Much of the evidence presented consisted of secret wire-tappings from [[United States|U.S.]] and [[Germany|German]] intelligence sources. In the recordings Abdulla and Berzengi used coded language to describe the attacks. Berzengi, who according to the court was the leading of the two, was sentenced to seven years of imprisonment and Abdulla to six years.<ref>{{cite news|first=Stefan |last=Lisinski |title=L\u00e5nga straff f\u00f6r terrorbrott |url=http://www.dn.se/DNet/jsp/polopoly.jsp?d=147&a=414181&previousRenderType=8 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901104041/http://www.dn.se/DNet/jsp/polopoly.jsp?d=147&a=414181&previousRenderType=8 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-09-01 |newspaper=[[Dagens Nyheter]] |date=2005-05-12 |accessdate=2007-01-22 |language=sv}}</ref> The [[Svea Court of Appeal]] later reduced the sentences to five years for Berzengi and four and a half year for Abdulla.<ref>{{cite news|title=Terrorister fick s\u00e4nkta straff i hovr\u00e4tten|url=http://www.sr.se/Ekot/arkiv.asp?DagensDatum=2005-10-03&Artikel=705027|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001002630/http://www.sr.se/Ekot/arkiv.asp?DagensDatum=2005-10-03&Artikel=705027|url-status=dead|archive-date=2007-10-01|publisher=[[Ekot]]|date=2005-10-03|accessdate=2007-01-22|language=sv}}</ref> The appeal to the [[Supreme Court of Sweden|Supreme Court]] was denied.<ref>{{cite news|title=HD pr\u00f6var inte terroristm\u00e5let |url=http://www.sr.se/ekot/arkiv.asp?DagensDatum=2005-11-21&Artikel=738229 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313042421/http://www.sr.se/EKOT/arkiv.asp?DagensDatum=2005-11-21&Artikel=738229 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-03-13 |publisher=[[Ekot]] |date=2005-11-21 |accessdate=2007-01-22 |language=sv}}</ref> The both are also to be deported back to Iraq after serving their sentences in Sweden. Abdulla is currently serving his sentence at the Norrk\u00f6ping Prison.<ref name=sydsvenskan />\n\nThe conviction of Berzengi and Abdulla was the first since the new Swedish terrorism legislation was taken into effect on July 1, 2003. It was also the first ever conviction in [[Western Europe]] of people financing terrorism.<ref name=sydsvenskan />\n\n==Links to al-Qaeda==\nAnsar's first leader, [[Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i]], was trained by al-Qaeda in Afghanistan.<ref name=Canadian />\nAnother early leader of Ansar, Abu Abdul Rahman, killed in October 2001, had, to the conviction of the U.S. government, also ties to al-Qaeda.<ref name=Canadian />\nIn a report dated July 31, 2002, the U.S. [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] (DIA) concluded: \"Ansar al-Islam is an independent organization that receives assistance from al-Qaeda, but is not a branch of the group.\"<ref name=DIAjul2002 />\n\nBegin 2003, less than 10 percent of individuals in Ansar were both Taliban and al-Qaeda members.<ref name=Canadian />\nThis, and the information about Shafi'i and Rahman, led the U.S. government, in January 2003, to proclaim, by the mouth of [[Colin Powell|Secretary of State Colin Powell]], that a 'link' between Ansar and al-Qaeda exists,<ref name=Canadian /> and that the U.S. was preparing to unveil new evidence of it.<ref name=Bbc31-1-3>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/2713749.stm|work=BBC News|title=Mullah denies Iraq al-Qaeda link|date=31 January 2003|author=O'Toole, Pam|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nMullah Krekar in January 2003 denied links of Ansar with al-Qaeda.<ref name=Bbc31-1-3 />\nU.S. terrorism expert [[Rohan Gunaratna]] in January 2003 however disagreed with Krekar and affirmed links of Ansar with al-Qaeda: \"Ansar al-Islam has links with al-Qaeda \u2013 in fact it is an associate group of al-Qaeda\".<ref name=Bbc31-1-3 />\nIn March\u2013April 2003, Mullah Krekar again protested against such links, and said to newspaper ''[[Al-Hayat]]'' that he had contacts with the American government prior to 11 September 2001, and possessed \"irrefutable evidence against the Americans and I am prepared to supply it \u2026 if [the U.S.] tries to implicate me in an affair linked to terrorism\".<ref name=Canadian />\n\n==Designation as a terrorist organization==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n|Country\n|Date\n|References\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Australia}}\n|March 2003\n|<ref name=\"australia-2014-01-22\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalsecurity.gov.au/agd/WWW/NationalSecurity.nsf/Page/What_Governments_are_doingListing_of_Terrorism_Organisations |title=Listing of terrorist organisations |accessdate=2014-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111151526/http://www.nationalsecurity.gov.au/agd/WWW/NationalSecurity.nsf/Page/What_Governments_are_doingListing_of_Terrorism_Organisations |archivedate=November 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Canada}}\n|17 May 2004\n|<ref name=\"canada-2014-01-22\">{{cite web |url=http://www.publicsafety.gc.ca/cnt/ntnl-scrt/cntr-trrrsm/lstd-ntts/crrnt-lstd-ntts-eng.aspx |title=Currently listed entities |author= |date= |website= |publisher= |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Israel}}\n|2005\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov.il/NR/rdonlyres/9C960928-70AB-428A-BCCC-2E6091F2BDE3/40880/impa_terror_eng_17012013.doc |title=Archived copy |accessdate=August 9, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810135338/http://www.justice.gov.il/NR/rdonlyres/9C960928-70AB-428A-BCCC-2E6091F2BDE3/40880/impa_terror_eng_17012013.doc |archivedate=August 10, 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|United Kingdom}}\n|14 October 2005\n|<ref>{{cite act |title=[[Terrorism Act 2000]] |number=11 |year=2000 |article=2 |articletype=Schedule |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2000/11/schedule/2}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|United States}}\n|22 March 2004\n|<ref name=\"us-fto\">{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/ct/rls/other/des/123085.htm|title=Foreign Terrorist Organizations|author= |date=2012-09-28 |website= |publisher= |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|UAE}}\n|16 November 2014\n|<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395272478814 | title=UAE Cabinet approves list of designated terrorist organisations, groups}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|IRQ}}\n|\n|<ref>https://baghdadtoday.news/ar/news/35233/\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0646\u064a\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0629-\u062a\u062d\u0630\u0631-\u0645\u0646-\u0648\u062c\u0648\u062f-\u0646\u0634\u0627\u0637\u0627\u062a-\u0627\u0631\u0647\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0629-\u0642\u0631\u0628-\u062d\u0644\u0628\u062c\u0629-\u0627\u062d\u0630\u0631\u0648\u0627-\u0627\u0646\u0635\u0627\u0631-\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645-\u0648\u0627\u0646\u062a\u062d\u0627\u0631\u064a\u064a-\u0627\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646</ref>\n|-\n|{{JPN}}\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.moj.go.jp/psia/ITH/organizations/index.html | title=\u56fd\u969b\u30c6\u30ed\u7d44\u7e54 \u4e16\u754c\u306e\u30c6\u30ed\u7d44\u7e54\u7b49\u306e\u6982\u8981\u30fb\u52d5\u5411 &#124; \u56fd\u969b\u30c6\u30ed\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u8981\u89a7\uff08Web\u7248\uff09 &#124; \u516c\u5b89\u8abf\u67fb\u5e81}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Leadership==\nAnsar's first leader until shortly after 11 September 2001 was Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i.<ref name=Canadian>{{cite news|last1=Ram|first1=Sunil|title=The Enemy of My Enemy: The odd link between Ansar al-Islam, Iraq and Iran|url=http://www.ciss.ca/Comment_EnemyofMyEnemy.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040330135055/http://www.ciss.ca/Comment_EnemyofMyEnemy.pdf|archivedate=30 March 2004|accessdate=6 February 2015|publisher=The Canadian Institute of Strategic Studies|date=April 2003}}</ref>\n\n[[Mullah Krekar]] in 2001 replaced Shafi'i as leader of Ansar, Shafi'i became his deputy.<ref name=Canadian />\nAfter Mullah Krekar left for Norway in 2003, Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i was again the leader of Ansar al-Islam.<ref name=Presstv8-8-12>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=125357&sectionid=351020201 |title=No Operation |publisher=Presstv.ir |accessdate=2012-08-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930000329/http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=125357&sectionid=351020201 |archivedate=September 30, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2010 Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i was captured by US forces in Baghdad.<ref name=Presstv8-8-12 />\nOn December 15, 2011 Ansar al-Islam announced a new emir, Sheikh Abu Hashim al Ibrahim<ref name=lwjjan2012>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2012/01/ansar_al_islam_names.php |title=Ansar al Islam names new leader|website=Long War Journal|date=2012-01-05 |accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref>\nA history of the group published on Twitter in November, 2015 by Abu al-Waleed al-Salafi states that \"a number of leaders of the group, including Abu Hashim Al Ibrahim, the amir of the group,\" were arrested \"at the beginning of 2014\"; the article does not at all suggest that any replacement emir had been appointed.<ref name=\"complete history\" />\n\n==Claimed and alleged attacks==\nAnsar al-Islam detonated a suicide car bomb on March 22, 2003, killing [[Australia]]n journalist [[Paul Moran (photojournalist)|Paul Moran]] and several others. The group was also thought to have been responsible for a September 9, 2003 attempted bombing of a [[United States Department of Defense]] office in [[Erbil]], which killed three people.\n\nOn February 1, 2004 suicide bombings hit parallel [[Eid al-Fitr|Eid]]-celebrations arranged by the two main Kurdish parties, PUK and [[Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iraq]] (KDP), in the Kurdish capital of [[Erbil]], killing 109 and wounding more than 200 partygoers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rudaw.net/english/kurdistan/01022019 |date=2019-02-01 |accessdate=2019-02-01 |title=PM Barzani stresses KDP-PUK unity 15 years after Erbil bombings |work=Rudaw}}</ref> Responsibility for this attack was claimed by the then unknown group [[Ansar al-Sunnah]], and stated to be in support of \"our brothers in Ansar al-Islam\".\n\nIn November 2008, an archbishop in [[Mosul]] received a threat signed by the \"Ansar al-Islam brigades\", warning all Christians to leave Iraq or else be killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pukmedia.com/english/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7622&Itemid=53 |title=\u0645\u06d5\u06a9\u062a\u06d5\u0628\u06cc \u0631\u0627\u06af\u06d5\u06cc\u0627\u0646\u062f\u0646\u06cc \u06cc\u06d5\u06a9\u06ce\u062a\u06cc\u06cc \u0646\u06cc\u0634\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u06cc \u06a9\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 |publisher=PUKmedia |accessdate=2012-08-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218201820/http://pukmedia.com/english/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7622&Itemid=53 |archivedate=February 18, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nStabbing attack on police officer in Berlin on September 17, 2015 by Ansar operative [[Rafik Yousef]].<ref name=Huggler>{{cite news|last1=Huggler|first1=Justin|title=Islamic terrorist shot dead after Berlin attack on policewoman|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/11872727/Islamic-terrorist-shot-dead-after-Berlin-attack-on-policewoman.html |accessdate=17 September 2015|work=Telegraph|date=17 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=StabbingPolicewoman>{{cite news|title=Iraqi man shot dead in Berlin after stabbing policewoman |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/17/iraqi-man-shot-dead-in-berlin-after-stabbing-policewoman|accessdate=17 September 2015|agency=Agence France|work=The Guardian |date=17 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/11872727/Islamic-terrorist-shot-dead-after-Berlin-attack-on-policewoman.html |title=Islamic terrorist shot dead after Berlin attack on policewoman|date=17 September 2015|work=Telegraph|accessdate=3 April 2016|last1=Huggler|first1=Justin}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books\n |1=Islamic terrorism\n |3=Islamic terrorist groups\n}}\n* [[Islamic Movement in Kurdistan]]\n* [[Kurdistan Islamic Union|Islamic Union of Kurdistan]]\n* [[Islamic Group Kurdistan|Islamic Group of Kurdistan]]\n* [[Islamic Kurdish League]]\n* [[Jamaat Ansar al-Sunna]]\n* [[Kurdish Revolutionary Hezbollah]]\n* [[Islamic Kurdistan Party|Partiya \u0130slamiya Kurdistan]]\n* [[(Turkish) Kurdish-Hizbullah]]\n* [[Islamic Kurdish Society]]\n* [[Islamic Fayli Grouping in Iraq]]\n* [[List of armed groups in the Iraqi Civil War]]\n* [[Al-Nusra Front]]\n* [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]\n* [[Rawti Shax]]\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/01402390902987046 Micah Zenko (2009) Foregoing Limited Force: The George W. Bush Administration's Decision Not to Attack Ansar Al-Islam, Journal of Strategic Studies, 32:4, 615-649]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.csmonitor.com/2003/1016/p12s01-woiq.htm The Rise and Fall of Ansar al-Islam], Christian Science Monitor\n* [http://www.cfr.org/publication/9237/ansar_alislam_iraq_islamistskurdish_separatists_.html Ansar al-Islam terrorist attacks]\n* [https://www.hrw.org/backgrounder/mena/ansarbk020503.htm Human Rights Watch: Ansar al-Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060224225910/http://www.crisisgroup.org/home/index.cfm?id=2104&l=1 Radical Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan: Ansar al-Islam]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/2730253.stm Zarqawi and the 'al-Qaeda link'], February 5, 2003.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041110052354/http://www.aftenposten.no/english/local/article513564.ece Mullah Krekar arrested]( ), March 21, 2003.\n* [http://schanzer.pundicity.com/592/ansar-al-islam-postmortem-or-prelude-to-more Ansar al-Islam: Postmortem or Prelude to More Attacks?], April 3, 2003.\n* [http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,426910,00.html Time.com article on first AI suicide attack], February 26, 2003\n* [http://schanzer.pundicity.com/582/ansar-al-islam-iraqs-al-qaeda-connection Ansar al-Islam: Iraq's al-Qaeda Connection], January 15, 2003\n* [https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2003/17823.htm State Department Designation of Ansar Al-Islam, February 20, 2003]\n* [https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2004/30649.htm Foreign Terrorist Organizations: Designation of Ansar al-Islam (Al), Redesignation of Three Others (State Department), March 22, 2004]\n* [http://www.athenaintelligence.org/index2.html Athena Intelligence] Advanced Research Network on Insurgency and Terrorism\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090415022232/http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2002/03/25/020325fa_FACT1 The Great Terror], The New Yorker\n* [http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2003/02/10/030210fa_fact The Unknown: The C.I.A. and the Pentagon take another look at Al Qaeda and Iraq], The New Yorker\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041015080217/http://www.insightnewstv.com/d80/ Mullah Krekar Interview]\n\n{{Armed Iraqi Groups in the Iraq War and the Iraq Civil War}}\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Militant Islamism}}\n\n[[Category:Iraqi insurgency (2003\u20132011)]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Japan]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Israel]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Canada]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Australia]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist in Asia]]\n[[Category:Groups affiliated with al-Qaeda]]\n[[Category:Salafi groups]]\n[[Category:Anti-government factions of the Syrian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Factions in the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Jihadist groups in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Jihadist groups in Syria]]\n[[Category:Paramilitary organizations based in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Iraq]]\n", "text_old": "{{Hatnote|Not to be confused with [[Jabhat Ansar al-Islam]].}}\n{{Infobox War Faction\n|name=Ansar al-Islam\n|native_name = \u062c\u0645\u0627\u0639\u0629 \u0623\u0646\u0635\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\n|native_name_lang = Ar\n|war = the [[Iraq War]], [[Iraqi insurgency (post-U.S. withdrawal)|Iraqi insurgency]], [[Syrian Civil War]], and the [[War on Terror|Global War on Terrorism]]\n|image = [[File:Flag of Ansar al-Islam.svg|border|200px]]\n|caption = The Flag of Ansar al-Islam \u2013 al Sahab<ref name=lwjjan2012 />\n|active = September 2001 \u2013 29 August 2014 <small>(main faction)</small><br />\n29 August 2014\u2013''present'' <small>(independent pro-AQ Iraqi and Syrian factions)</small><ref name=\"al-monitor.com\">{{cite web|title=IS disciplines some emirs to avoid losing base|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/security/2014/09/is-takfiri-caliphate.html#|date=2 September 2014|accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"israelnationalnews.com\">{{cite web|title=Iraqi Jihadist Group Swears Alleigance to Islamic State|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/184544#.VAxa5xagSSk|date=29 August 2014|accessdate= 2 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"broken\">{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2016/08/jihadists-and-other-rebels-claim-to-have-broken-through-siege-of-aleppo.php|title=Jihadists and other rebels claim to have broken through siege of Aleppo|author=Thomas Joscelyn|work=The Long War Journal|date=7 August 2016|accessdate=7 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"new name\" />\n|ideology = [[Salafism]]\n*[[Salafist Jihadism]]\n*[[Wahhabism]]<ref name=hrwa>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/backgrounder/mena/ansarbk020503.htm|title=Ansar al-Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan|work=[[Human Rights Watch]]}}</ref>\n|leaders = [[Mullah Krekar]] <small>(2001\u201303)</small><br />[[Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i]]{{POW}} <small>(2003\u201310)</small><br />[[Abu Hashim al-Ibrahim]] <small>(2010\u201314)</small><ref name=lwjjan2012 />\n|headquarters = [[Hamrin Mountains]]<ref name=\"new name\">{{cite web|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/1208661/middle-east#.WjGjatHn6gc.twitter |title=Kurdish militant group re-emerges in northern Iraq under new name |author=Suadad al-Salhy |work=Arab News |date=14 December 2017 |accessdate=14 December 2017 }}</ref>\n|area = [[Iraqi Kurdistan]],<ref name=hrwa /> [[Iraq]], [[Syria]]\n|strength = Before split: 350+<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtoninstitute.org/uploads/Documents/opeds/4224e31e5fa37.pdf|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref><br />2017: Hundreds <small>(acc. to Iraqi officials)</small><ref name=\"new name\" />\n|clans = [[White Flags]] <small>(Iraqi gov. claim)</small><ref name=\"new name\" />\n|partof = [[Rouse the Believers Operations Room]]<ref name=\"joint room\">{{cite web|url=http://nedaa-sy.com/en/news/9078|title=Military groups calling themselves \"the finest factions of the Levant\" form joint operations room|publisher=Syria Call|date=15 October 2018|accessdate=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n|previous = Jund al-Islam\n|became = {{flag|Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant}} <small>(main faction)</small><ref name=\"isis\" /><br />{{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban (original).svg|border}} [[White Flags]] <small>(Splinter faction, Iraqi government claim, since 2017)</small>\n|allies = {{flag|al-Qaeda}}<ref name=\"iraqiupdate\">{{cite web|title=Key Updates on Iraq's Sunni Insurgent Groups|url=http://brown-moses.blogspot.co.uk/2014/05/key-updates-on-iraqs-sunni-insurgent.html|author=Aymenn Jawad Al-Tamimi|publisher=Brown Moses Blog|date=11 May 2014|accessdate=26 May 2014}}</ref><br>{{flagdeco|ISIL}} [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]<ref>https://www.pri.org/stories/2014-07-21/youve-heard-about-isis-you-havent-heard-about-these-guys</ref><br/>{{flagicon image|Flag of Hayat Tahrir al-Sham.svg}} [[Tahrir al-Sham]]<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of Turkistan Islamic Party.svg}} [[Turkistan Islamic Party]]<br>{{flagicon image|Infobox Ajnad al-Kavkaz flag.png}} [[Ajnad al-Kavkaz]]<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of the Kurdistan Islamic Group.svg}} [[Kurdistan Islamic Group]]<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of the Islamic Front (Syria) (Black).svg}} [[Islamic Front (Syria)|Islamic Front]] <small>(2013\u20132015)</small><br>[[Guardians of Religion Organization]]<br>{{flagicon image|Emblem of the Ansar al-Deen Front.svg}} [[Ansar al-Din Front]]\n<br>{{flagdeco|Syrian Opposition}} [[Free Syrian Army]]<br>{{flag|Iran}} <small>(allegedly)</small><ref>https://jamestown.org/program/the-hidden-hand-of-iran-in-the-resurgence-of-ansar-al-islam/</ref>\n|opponents = \n{{flagdeco|Kurdistan}} [[Peshmerga]]<br>{{IRQ}}<br>{{SYR}}<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of Syrian Democratic Forces.svg}} [[Syrian Democratic Forces]]<br>{{USA}}<br>{{flag|Iran}}<br>{{flagicon image|InfoboxHez.PNG}} [[Hezbollah]]<br>{{flag|Russia}}\n|battles = [[Iraq War]]\n*[[Kurdistan Islamist conflict]]\n[[Syrian Civil War]]\n*[[Battle of Aleppo (2012\u20132016)]]\n**[[2016 Aleppo summer campaign]]\n*[[2018 Idlib demilitarization]]<ref name=\"joint room\" />\n*[[Northwestern Syria offensive (April 2019\u2013present)]]\n[[Iraqi Civil War (2014\u20132017)]]\n}}\n\n'''Ansar al-Islam''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0646\u0635\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645}} ''{{transl|ar|An\u1e63\u0101r al-Isl\u0101m}}'') or '''Ansar al-Islam fi Kurdistan''' ({{lang-ar|\u0623\u0646\u0635\u0627\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0625\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645 \u0641\u064a \u0643\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646}} ''{{transl|ar|An\u1e63\u0101r al-Isl\u0101m f\u012b Kurdist\u0101n}}''),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/legacy/backgrounder/mena/ansarbk020503.htm|title=Ansar al-Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan (Human Rights Watch Backgrounder, )}}</ref> also referred to as '''AAI''',<ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\">Chalk, Peter, ''Encyclopedia of Terrorism'' Volume 1, 2012, ABC-CLIO</ref> is a [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] [[Muslim]] [[insurgent]] group in Iraq<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fas.org/irp/world/para/ansar.htm |title=Ansar al-Islam |publisher=Federation of American Scientists |date= |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref> and Syria.<ref name=iraqiupdate /> It was established in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]] by former al-Qaeda members in 2001 as a [[Salafist]] [[Islamist]] movement that imposed a strict application of [[Sharia]] in villages it controlled around Biyara to the northeast of [[Halabja]], near the Iranian border. Its ideology follows a [[Athari|literal]] interpretation of the Koran and promotes a return to what it claims is the example of the first Muslims ([[Salaf]]).<ref>[http://atimes.com/atimes/Middle_East/FA09Ak02.html ''Asia Times'': \"Ansar al-Islam refuses to lie down\" by Valentinas Mite] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208224138/http://atimes.com/atimes/Middle_East/FA09Ak02.html |date=2015-12-08 }} January 9, 2004</ref> Following the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], the group became an insurgent group which fought against the Kurdish government, [[Multi-National Force \u2013 Iraq|American led forces]] and their Iraqi allies. The group continued to fight the Iraqi Government following the [[withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq]], and sent members to Syria to fight the Government following the outbreak of the [[Syrian Civil War]].\n\nThe group was a [[List of designated terrorist organizations|designated terrorist organization]]<!-- see link for inclusion of national bodies --> in the United Nations, Australia, Canada, Israel, the United Kingdom and the United States, and a known affiliate of the [[al-Qaeda]] network.<ref>Schanzer, Jonathan. ''Al-Qaeda's armies: Middle East affiliate groups & the next generation of terror''. Specialist Press International. New York, 2005.</ref>\n\nOn 29 August 2014, a statement on the behalf of 50 leaders and members of Ansar al-Islam announced that the group was merging with the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]], thereby officially dissolving the organization.<ref name=\"isis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/security/2014/09/is-takfiri-caliphate.html#|title=IS disciplines some emirs to avoid losing base \u2013 Al-Monitor: the Pulse of the Middle East|work=Al-Monitor|date=2014-09-02}}</ref><ref name=\"isis1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.israelnationalnews.com/News/News.aspx/184544#.VAxa5xagSSk|title=Jihadist Group Swears Loyalty to Islamic State \u2013 Middle East \u2013 News \u2013 Arutz Sheva|work=Arutz Sheva|accessdate=7 November 2014}}</ref> However, some small elements within Ansar al-Islam rejected this merger, and continued to function as an independent organization.<ref name=\"isis\" /> When a previously unknown Kurdish militant [[White Flags|group using white flags]] appeared in Iraq in 2017, Iraqi security and intelligence officials argued that this was a [[front organization]] of Ansar al-Islam, which reportedly still had hundreds of fighters operating in the [[Hamrin Mountains]].<ref name=\"new name\" />\n\n==History==\n\n===Formation===\nAnsar al-Islam was formed in September 2001 from a merger of Jund al-Islam (Soldiers of Islam), led by [[Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i]], and a splinter group from the [[Kurdistan Islamic Movement]] led by [[Mullah Krekar]]. Krekar became the leader of the merged Ansar al-Islam, which opposed an agreement made between IMK and the dominant Kurdish group in the area, [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] (PUK). The group later made an allegiance to al-Qaeda and allegedly received direct funds from the terror network.<ref>''Terrorism & Its Effects''. Sanchez, Juan. Global Media, 2007.</ref>\n\nThe two IMK splinter groups that formed Jund al Islam on 1 September 2001, had some early battlefield successes in the same month when it killed 42 PUK fighters in an ambush, which led to them drawing in more IMK leaders their ranks, on 10 December 2001, the group became known as AAI (Ansar al-Islam ).<ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\" />\n\nAnsar al-Islam initially comprised approximately 300 men, many of them veterans of the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]], and a proportion being neither Kurd nor Arab. During its stay in the Biyara region near the Iranian border, there were allegations of logistical support from \"powerful factions in Iran\".<ref name=\"crisisgroup\">{{cite web |url=http://www.crisisgroup.org/en/regions/middle-east-north-africa/iraq-iran-gulf/iraq/B004-radical-islam-in-iraqi-kurdistan-the-mouse-that-roared.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111121202552/http://www.crisisgroup.org/en/regions/middle-east-north-africa/iraq-iran-gulf/iraq/B004-radical-islam-in-iraqi-kurdistan-the-mouse-that-roared.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=2011-11-21 |title=Radical Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan: The Mouse that Roared?|publisher=International Crisis Group |date=2014-02-07 |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n\nThe roots of Ansar al-Islam can be traced to the mid-1990s. The group consists of various Islamist factions that splintered from the Islamic Movement of Kurdistan (IMK). In 2001, shortly before the 9/11 attacks, leaders of several Kurdish Islamist factions visited the al-Qa'ida leadership in Afghanistan planning to create a base for al-Qa'ida in northern Iraq. A document found in Kabul stated the groups' objectives, which was to \"\"expel those Jews and Christians from Kurdistan and join the way of jihad, [and] rule every piece of land \u2026 with the Islamic Shari'a rule.\" This was also confirmed by the ''Los Angeles Times'', based upon interviews with an Ansar prisoner, which stated that in October 2000, Kurdish Islamist leaders sent jihadists to bin Laden's camps. They received the message from bin Laden that Kurdish Islamic cells should unite.<ref>[http://www.meforum.org/579/ansar-al-islam-back-in-iraq Ansar al-Islam: Back in Iraq :: Middle East Quarterly<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Period up to the Iraq War===\nUpon its founding, Ansar al-Islam declared war on all secular political parties in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]], throughout 2002, AAI carried out attacks and targeting killings of these Kurdish groups, particularly high-level PUK members, as well as engaging in battles and skirmishes with the PUK. The attacks allowed the AAI to carve out space to impose its form of Islamist governance in northeast Iraq under its spiritual founder and leader [[Mullah Krekar]]. [[Sharia Law]] was implemented, enforcing it through bombing of businesses it deemed in-Islamic, acid attacks on women it deemed immodest and beheading of those it deemed apostates.<ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\" />\n\nVillagers under Ansar al-Islam's control were subjected to harsh sharia laws; musical instruments were destroyed and singing forbidden. The only school for girls in the area was destroyed, and all pictures of women removed from merchandise labels. Sufi shrines were desecrated and members of the Kaka'i (a religious group also known as [[Ahl-e Haqq]]) were forced to convert to Islam or flee. Former prisoners of the group also claim that Ansar al-Islam routinely used torture and severe beatings when interrogating prisoners. Beheading of prisoners had also been reported.<ref name=\"hrw\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/backgrounder/mena/ansarbk020503.htm |title=Ansar al-Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan |publisher=Human Rights Watch |date= |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2001 and early 2002, the AAI received an inflow of foreign (mostly Arab) jihadists fleeing Afghanistan following the [[United States invasion of Afghanistan|2001 invasion of Afghanistan]], including [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]].<ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\" />\n\nPrior to the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|US 2003 invasion of Iraq]], Paramilitary teams from the [[Special Activities Division]] (SAD) and the Army's [[10th Special Forces Group (United States)|10th Special Forces Group]] entered Iraq and cooperated with [[Patriotic Union of Kurdistan]] [[Peshmerga]] to attack Ansar al-Islam. Together they launched [[Operation Viking Hammer]] in March 2003 which dealt a huge blow to the terrorist group which resulted in the deaths of a substantial number of terrorists and the uncovering of a [[Chemical warfare|chemical weapons]] facility at Sargat.<ref>''Plan of Attack'', [[Bob Woodward]], Simon and Schuster, 2004.</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.kurdistan24.net/en/news/ccbc37f1-3955-4a19-a72d-a7c210a6a036 |title = Pentagon: US in Syria 'for the long haul;' hails Peshmerga in 'Operation Viking Hammer'}}</ref> Sargat was the only facility of its type discovered in Iraq.<ref>{{cite book |title=Operation Hotel California: The Clandestine War inside Iraq |first=Mike |last=Tucker |author2=Charles Faddis |year=2008 |publisher=The Lyons Press |isbn=978-1-59921-366-8 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/operationhotelca00tuck }}</ref><ref>[http://wamu.org/audio/dr/08/10/r2081007-22101.asx An interview on public radio with the author] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110930081326/http://wamu.org/audio/dr/08/10/r2081007-22101.asx |date=September 30, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\" />\n\n===Iraq War===\n{{further|Ansar al-Sunna}}\nIn September 2003, members of Ansar al-Islam who had fled to [[Iran]] after the 2003 joint operation by Iraqi and US forces against them announced the creation of a group called [[Jamaat Ansar al-Sunna]], which was dedicated to expelling U.S. occupation forces from Iraq. Ansar al-Sunna became a prominent insurgent group active in the so-called [[Sunni Triangle]], carrying out kidnappings, suicide bombings, and guerilla attacks.\n\nIn November or December 2007 the [[Ansar al-Sunna]] group formally acknowledged being derived from Ansar al-Islam, and reverted to using that name.<ref name=\"Chalk, Peter 2012\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://counterterrorismblog.org/2007/12/ansar_alsunnah_acknowledges_re.php |archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20091013162709/http://counterterrorismblog.org/2007/12/ansar_alsunnah_acknowledges_re.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-10-13 |title=Ansar al-Sunnah Acknowledges Relationship with Ansar al-Islam, Reverts to Using Ansar al-Islam Name |publisher=Counterterrorism Blog |accessdate=2012-08-08}}</ref>\n\n===Iraqi Insurgency (post-U.S. withdrawal)===\nAnsar al-Islam remained active after the [[withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq]] of 2011, taking part in the [[Iraqi insurgency (post-U.S. withdrawal)|insurgency]] against Iraq's central government. Attacks against Iraqi security forces have been claimed by the group, particularly around [[Mosul]] and [[Kirkuk]].<ref name=iraqiupdate />\n\n===Syrian Civil War===\nAnsar al-Islam has established a presence in Syria to take part in the [[Syrian Civil War]], initially under the name of \"Ansar al-Sham\",<ref>{{cite web|title=Musings of an Iraqi Brasenostril on Jihad: Comprehensive Reference Guide to Sunni Militant Groups in Iraq|url=http://jihadology.net/2014/01/23/musings-of-an-iraqi-brasenostril-on-jihad-comprehensive-reference-guide-to-sunni-militant-groups-in-iraq/|author=Aymenn Jawad Al-Tamimi|publisher=Jihadology.net|date=23 January 2014|accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> later under its own name. The group coordinated with the [[Ahfad al-Rasul Brigades]] to bomb [[Syrian Armed Forces|Syrian military]] compounds in [[Damascus]] in August 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-syria-crisis-explosion/bomb-explosion-hits-security-area-of-damascus-activists-idUSBRE89A1CB20121011|title=Bomb explosion hits security area of Damascus: activists|newspaper=[[Reuters]]|date=12 October 2012}}</ref> It also played a role in the [[Battle of Aleppo (2012\u2013present)|Battle of Aleppo]] and coordinates with other Salafist groups including al-Qaeda's [[al-Nusra Front]] and the [[Islamic Front (Syria)|Islamic Front]].<ref name=\"iraqiupdate\" /> The Syrian Ansar al-Islam units in Aleppo remained independent when the main faction joined ISIL in 2014.<ref name=\"complete history\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aymennjawad.org/2015/12/a-complete-history-of-jamaat-ansar-al-islam |title=A Complete History of Jamaat Ansar al-Islam}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, they fought alongside the al-Nusra Front during a [[Aleppo offensive (June\u2013August 2016)|major offensive]] in the city.<ref name=\"broken\" /> A military commander of the group, Abu Layth al-Tunisi, was reportedly killed in combat during this operation, probably southwest of Aleppo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/top-salafist-commander-killed-southern-aleppo/|title=Top salafist commander killed in southern Aleppo|first=Zen|last=Adra|work=[[Al-Masdar News]]|date=20 August 2016|accessdate=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://syrianperspective.com/2016/08/terrorist-numbers-drying-up-in-aleppo-as-syrian-army-kills-over-60-syrian-army-slashes-rodents-in-hama-major-advance-in-daarayyaa-snafu-at-idlib-crossing.html#dblFlZYx1pGMCUG5.99 |title=Terrorist Numbers Drying Up In Aleppo as Syrian Army Kills Over 60|date=2016-08-20}}</ref> By July 2018, the Syrian faction of Ansar al-Islam (not to be confused with the Syrian [[Ansar al-Sham]] group, which fought in the same area) was active in [[Latakia Governorate]], raiding local Syrian Army outposts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2018/07/ansar-al-islam-raids-assad-regime-position-in-latakia.php |title=Ansar al-Islam raids Assad regime position in Latakia |author=Thomas Joscelyn |work=[[Long War Journal]] |date=11 July 2018 |accessdate=14 July 2018 }}</ref> Following the Turkish-Russian agreement to [[2018 Idlib demilitarization|demilitarize Idlib]] in September 2018, the Syrian branch of Ansar al-Islam joined the [[Rouse the Believers Operations Room]] with other al-Qaeda-linked groups to oppose any attempts to carry out the demilitarization of northwestern Syria.<ref name=\"joint room\" />\n\n===Reported re-emergence in Iraq===\n{{further|White Flags}}\nAfter the defeat of ISIL and the capture of [[Tuz Khurmatu]] by Turkmen and Shiite [[Popular Mobilization Forces]] during the [[2017 Iraqi\u2013Kurdish conflict]], the town and its surroundings came under almost daily rocket attacks by a militant faction that used a white flag with the black head of a lion. These \"[[White Flags]]\", led by Assi Al-Qawali, reportedly consisted of Kurdish militants, ex-ISIL fighters and [[Kurdistan Democratic Party]] supporters who claimed to be fighting to \"liberate the Kurdish lands\u2014occupied by the Iranian Shiite militias\". Iraqi security and intelligence officials said that intelligence reports made it likely that this new group was a [[front organization]] of Ansar al-Islam, which reportedly still had hundreds of fighters operating in the [[Hamrin Mountains]].<ref name=\"new name\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebaghdadpost.com/en/story/22911/Iraqi-security-forces-repel-White-Flags-terrorists-in-Tuz-Khurmatu |title=Iraqi security forces repel White Flags terrorists in Tuz Khurmatu |author= |work=[[The Baghdad Post]] |date=25 January 2018 |accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 October 2019, Ansar al-Islam claimed responsibility for an IED attack on a [[Popular Mobilization Forces]] vehicle in the [[Diyala Governorate]] in northeastern Iraq.<ref>https://jihadology.net/2019/10/30/new-statement-from-an%e1%b9%a3ar-al-islam-attack-in-iraq/</ref>\n\n==Alleged ties to Saddam Hussein's regime==\nIn a \"Special Analysis\" report dated July 31, 2002, the U.S. [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] (DIA) concluded the following regarding possible connections between Saddam's regime and Ansar al-Islam:\n\"The Iraqi regime seeks to influence and manipulate political events in the Kurdish-controlled north and probably has some type of assets in contact with Ansar al-Islam, either through liaison or through penetration by an intelligence asset.\"<ref name=DIAjul2002>DIA, Special Analysis, July 31, 2002, cited in [http://intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf Postwar Findings about Iraq's WMD Programs and Links to Terrorism and How they Compare with Prewar Assessments, pg. 71.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060921074629/http://intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf |date=September 21, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2003, the U.S. alleged that Ansar al-Islam provided a possible link between [[Saddam Hussein]] and al-Qaeda, and said to prepare to unveil new evidence of it.<ref name=Bbc31-1-3 />\nAnsar's leader [[Mullah Krekar]] in January 2003 denied links of Ansar with Saddam Hussein's government.<ref name=Bbc31-1-3 /> U.S. terrorism expert [[Rohan Gunaratna]] in January 2003 agreed with Krekar that links of Ansar with Iraqi Government were never proven.<ref name=Bbc31-1-3 />\n\nIn February 2003, then [[United States Secretary of State]] [[Colin Powell]] told the [[United Nations Security Council]], \"Baghdad has an agent in the most senior levels of the radical organization, Ansar al-Islam, that controls this corner of Iraq. In 2000 this agent offered Al Qaida safe haven in the region. After we swept Al Qaida from Afghanistan, some of its members accepted this safe haven.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=https://georgewbush-whitehouse.archives.gov/news/releases/2003/02/20030205-1.html | title=U.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell Addresses the U.N. Security Council | date=2003-02-05}}</ref>\n\nIn March\u2013April 2003, the BBC reported that a captured Iraqi intelligence officer had indicated that a senior Ansar leader, Abu Wail, was an Iraqi intelligence officer.<ref name=Canadian /> If that was true, then Saddam's regime had some influence on Ansar, said the BBC.<ref name=Canadian />\nSaddam's interest could have been to have Ansar as a force directly opposing Kurdish independence in northern Iraq, said the BBC.<ref name=Canadian />\n\nIn January 2004, Powell acknowledged that his speech of February 2003 presented no hard evidence of collaboration between Saddam and al-Qaeda; he told reporters at a State Department press conference that \"I have not seen smoking gun, concrete evidence about the connection, but I do believe the connections existed.\"<ref>NBC, MSNBC, AP, \"[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/ID/3909150/ No proof links Iraq, al-Qaeda, Powell says],\" MSNBC News Services (8 January 2004).</ref>\n\nThe [[Senate Report on Pre-war Intelligence on Iraq]], issued in 2004, concluded that Saddam \"was aware of Ansar al-Islam and [[al-Qaeda]] presence in northeastern Iraq, but the groups' presence was considered a threat to the regime and the Iraqi government attempted intelligence collection operations against them. The [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] (DIA) stated that information from senior Ansar al-Islam detainees revealed that the group viewed Saddam's regime as apostate, and denied any relationship with it.\"<ref>[http://intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf Senate Intelligence Committee Report p.92-93.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060921074629/http://intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf |date=September 21, 2006 }}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. [[United States Senate Select Committee on Intelligence|Select Committee on Intelligence]] in September 2006 again stated that: 'Postwar information reveals that Baghdad viewed Ansar al-Islam as a threat to the regime and (...) attempted to collect intelligence on the group'.<ref name=\"Conclusions\">{{cite news|title=Senate Select Committee on Intelligence on Postwar Findings About Iraq's WMD Programs and Links to Terrorism and How They Compare with Prewar Assessments. 109th Congress, 2nd Session |url=http://www.intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf |accessdate=8 February 2015 |publisher=[[Senate Report on Pre-war Intelligence on Iraq]] |date=8 September 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215060854/http://www.intelligence.senate.gov/phaseiiaccuracy.pdf |archivedate=February 15, 2015 }}(See III.G, Conclusions 5 and 6, p.109.)</ref>\n\nAfter Powell had left office, he in 2008 acknowledged that he was skeptical of the evidence presented to him for the speech of February 2003. In an interview, he told [[Barbara Walters]] then that he considered that speech a \"blot\" on his record and that he felt \"terrible\" about assertions that he made in the speech that turned out to be false. He said, \"There were some people in the intelligence community who knew at that time that some of these sources were not good, and shouldn't be relied upon, and they didn't speak up. That devastated me.\" When asked specifically about a Saddam/al-Qaeda connection, Powell responded, \"I have never seen a connection. \u2026 I can't think otherwise because I'd never seen evidence to suggest there was one.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=ABC News: Colin Powell on Iraq, Race, and Hurricane Relief|url=http://abcnews.go.com/2020/Politics/story?id=1105979&page=1|publisher=ABC News|date=2008-09-08|accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n\n==Swedish fund-raising case==\nAli Berzengi and Ferman Abdullah, the owner of a [[falafel]] stand in [[Stockholm]], raised money for what they claimed was poor children and Muslims. The money was then transferred through Abdulla's food stand, using the [[hawala]] transfer system.<ref name=sydsvenskan>{{cite news|author=L\u00f6nnaeus, Olle, Orrenius, Niklas, Magnusson, Erik |title=Kiosken var en terrorbank |url=http://sydsvenskan.se/sverige/article141850.ece |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060215223827/http://sydsvenskan.se/sverige/article141850.ece |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-02-15 |newspaper=[[Sydsvenskan]] |date=2006-02-12 |accessdate=2007-01-24 |language=sv}}</ref> The [[Swedish Security Service]] was informed in 2002 that people in Sweden had transferred money to Ansar al-Islam.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Swedish Security Service 2005|publisher=[[Swedish Security Service]]|year=2005|url=http://www.sakerhetspolisen.se/Publikationer/swedish_security_service_2005.pdf|accessdate=2007-01-22}} {{dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> On April 19, 2004, Berzengi and Abdulla were arrested along with another Iraqi, Shaho Shahab, and [[Lebanon|Lebanese]]-born Bilal Ramadan. Ramadan was released in September after a court found that there wasn't enough evidence to keep him in custody. Shahab was released in December after the government decided to deport him to Iraq. However, since Shahab risks receiving the death penalty in his home country, the deportation has not been carried out.<ref>{{cite news|title=Two Iraqis charged in Sweden with transferring money to al-Zarqawi|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2005-04-05-alzarqawi-money_x.htm|publisher=[[USA Today]]/[[Associated Press]]|date=2005-05-04|accessdate=2007-01-22}}</ref> In Abdulla's apartment the police found a letter from a man who claimed to have been in contact with [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]], the leader of [[al-Qaeda in Iraq]], as well as a detailed manual on how to use coded language.<ref name=sydsvenskan />\n\nOn May 12, 2005, Abdulla and Berzengi were convicted by the Stockholm District Court for \"planning of terrorist offences\" ({{lang-sv|f\u00f6rberedelse till terroristbrott}}) and \"planning of public devastation\" ({{lang-sv|f\u00f6rberedelse till allm\u00e4nfarlig \u00f6del\u00e4ggelse}}) according to [[Swedish law]]. Accord to the court they had transferred approximately one million [[Swedish krona|SEK]] to Ansar al-Islam. According to the court there was strong evidence that the collected money had the specific purpose of financing terrorist attacks. Much of the evidence presented consisted of secret wire-tappings from [[United States|U.S.]] and [[Germany|German]] intelligence sources. In the recordings Abdulla and Berzengi used coded language to describe the attacks. Berzengi, who according to the court was the leading of the two, was sentenced to seven years of imprisonment and Abdulla to six years.<ref>{{cite news|first=Stefan |last=Lisinski |title=L\u00e5nga straff f\u00f6r terrorbrott |url=http://www.dn.se/DNet/jsp/polopoly.jsp?d=147&a=414181&previousRenderType=8 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901104041/http://www.dn.se/DNet/jsp/polopoly.jsp?d=147&a=414181&previousRenderType=8 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2006-09-01 |newspaper=[[Dagens Nyheter]] |date=2005-05-12 |accessdate=2007-01-22 |language=sv}}</ref> The [[Svea Court of Appeal]] later reduced the sentences to five years for Berzengi and four and a half year for Abdulla.<ref>{{cite news|title=Terrorister fick s\u00e4nkta straff i hovr\u00e4tten|url=http://www.sr.se/Ekot/arkiv.asp?DagensDatum=2005-10-03&Artikel=705027|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001002630/http://www.sr.se/Ekot/arkiv.asp?DagensDatum=2005-10-03&Artikel=705027|url-status=dead|archive-date=2007-10-01|publisher=[[Ekot]]|date=2005-10-03|accessdate=2007-01-22|language=sv}}</ref> The appeal to the [[Supreme Court of Sweden|Supreme Court]] was denied.<ref>{{cite news|title=HD pr\u00f6var inte terroristm\u00e5let |url=http://www.sr.se/ekot/arkiv.asp?DagensDatum=2005-11-21&Artikel=738229 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070313042421/http://www.sr.se/EKOT/arkiv.asp?DagensDatum=2005-11-21&Artikel=738229 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-03-13 |publisher=[[Ekot]] |date=2005-11-21 |accessdate=2007-01-22 |language=sv}}</ref> The both are also to be deported back to Iraq after serving their sentences in Sweden. Abdulla is currently serving his sentence at the Norrk\u00f6ping Prison.<ref name=sydsvenskan />\n\nThe conviction of Berzengi and Abdulla was the first since the new Swedish terrorism legislation was taken into effect on July 1, 2003. It was also the first ever conviction in [[Western Europe]] of people financing terrorism.<ref name=sydsvenskan />\n\n==Links to al-Qaeda==\nAnsar's first leader, [[Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i]], was trained by al-Qaeda in Afghanistan.<ref name=Canadian />\nAnother early leader of Ansar, Abu Abdul Rahman, killed in October 2001, had, to the conviction of the U.S. government, also ties to al-Qaeda.<ref name=Canadian />\nIn a report dated July 31, 2002, the U.S. [[Defense Intelligence Agency]] (DIA) concluded: \"Ansar al-Islam is an independent organization that receives assistance from al-Qaeda, but is not a branch of the group.\"<ref name=DIAjul2002 />\n\nBegin 2003, less than 10 percent of individuals in Ansar were both Taliban and al-Qaeda members.<ref name=Canadian />\nThis, and the information about Shafi'i and Rahman, led the U.S. government, in January 2003, to proclaim, by the mouth of [[Colin Powell|Secretary of State Colin Powell]], that a 'link' between Ansar and al-Qaeda exists,<ref name=Canadian /> and that the U.S. was preparing to unveil new evidence of it.<ref name=Bbc31-1-3>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/2713749.stm|work=BBC News|title=Mullah denies Iraq al-Qaeda link|date=31 January 2003|author=O'Toole, Pam|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nMullah Krekar in January 2003 denied links of Ansar with al-Qaeda.<ref name=Bbc31-1-3 />\nU.S. terrorism expert [[Rohan Gunaratna]] in January 2003 however disagreed with Krekar and affirmed links of Ansar with al-Qaeda: \"Ansar al-Islam has links with al-Qaeda \u2013 in fact it is an associate group of al-Qaeda\".<ref name=Bbc31-1-3 />\nIn March\u2013April 2003, Mullah Krekar again protested against such links, and said to newspaper ''[[Al-Hayat]]'' that he had contacts with the American government prior to 11 September 2001, and possessed \"irrefutable evidence against the Americans and I am prepared to supply it \u2026 if [the U.S.] tries to implicate me in an affair linked to terrorism\".<ref name=Canadian />\n\n==Designation as a terrorist organization==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n|Country\n|Date\n|References\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Australia}}\n|March 2003\n|<ref name=\"australia-2014-01-22\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalsecurity.gov.au/agd/WWW/NationalSecurity.nsf/Page/What_Governments_are_doingListing_of_Terrorism_Organisations |title=Listing of terrorist organisations |accessdate=2014-01-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131111151526/http://www.nationalsecurity.gov.au/agd/WWW/NationalSecurity.nsf/Page/What_Governments_are_doingListing_of_Terrorism_Organisations |archivedate=November 11, 2013 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Canada}}\n|17 May 2004\n|<ref name=\"canada-2014-01-22\">{{cite web |url=http://www.publicsafety.gc.ca/cnt/ntnl-scrt/cntr-trrrsm/lstd-ntts/crrnt-lstd-ntts-eng.aspx |title=Currently listed entities |author= |date= |website= |publisher= |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|Israel}}\n|2005\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.justice.gov.il/NR/rdonlyres/9C960928-70AB-428A-BCCC-2E6091F2BDE3/40880/impa_terror_eng_17012013.doc |title=Archived copy |accessdate=August 9, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140810135338/http://www.justice.gov.il/NR/rdonlyres/9C960928-70AB-428A-BCCC-2E6091F2BDE3/40880/impa_terror_eng_17012013.doc |archivedate=August 10, 2014 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|United Kingdom}}\n|14 October 2005\n|<ref>{{cite act |title=[[Terrorism Act 2000]] |number=11 |year=2000 |article=2 |articletype=Schedule |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2000/11/schedule/2}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|United States}}\n|22 March 2004\n|<ref name=\"us-fto\">{{cite web|url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/ct/rls/other/des/123085.htm|title=Foreign Terrorist Organizations|author= |date=2012-09-28 |website= |publisher= |accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|UAE}}\n|16 November 2014\n|<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://wam.ae/en/details/1395272478814 | title=UAE Cabinet approves list of designated terrorist organisations, groups}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|IRQ}}\n|\n|<ref>https://baghdadtoday.news/ar/news/35233/\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0645\u0646-\u0627\u0644\u0646\u064a\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0629-\u062a\u062d\u0630\u0631-\u0645\u0646-\u0648\u062c\u0648\u062f-\u0646\u0634\u0627\u0637\u0627\u062a-\u0627\u0631\u0647\u0627\u0628\u064a\u0629-\u0642\u0631\u0628-\u062d\u0644\u0628\u062c\u0629-\u0627\u062d\u0630\u0631\u0648\u0627-\u0627\u0646\u0635\u0627\u0631-\u0627\u0644\u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645-\u0648\u0627\u0646\u062a\u062d\u0627\u0631\u064a\u064a-\u0627\u064a\u0631\u0627\u0646</ref>\n|-\n|{{JPN}}\n|\n|<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.moj.go.jp/psia/ITH/organizations/index.html | title=\u56fd\u969b\u30c6\u30ed\u7d44\u7e54 \u4e16\u754c\u306e\u30c6\u30ed\u7d44\u7e54\u7b49\u306e\u6982\u8981\u30fb\u52d5\u5411 &#124; \u56fd\u969b\u30c6\u30ed\u30ea\u30ba\u30e0\u8981\u89a7\uff08Web\u7248\uff09 &#124; \u516c\u5b89\u8abf\u67fb\u5e81}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Leadership==\nAnsar's first leader until shortly after 11 September 2001 was Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i.<ref name=Canadian>{{cite news|last1=Ram|first1=Sunil|title=The Enemy of My Enemy: The odd link between Ansar al-Islam, Iraq and Iran|url=http://www.ciss.ca/Comment_EnemyofMyEnemy.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040330135055/http://www.ciss.ca/Comment_EnemyofMyEnemy.pdf|archivedate=30 March 2004|accessdate=6 February 2015|publisher=The Canadian Institute of Strategic Studies|date=April 2003}}</ref>\n\n[[Mullah Krekar]] in 2001 replaced Shafi'i as leader of Ansar, Shafi'i became his deputy.<ref name=Canadian />\nAfter Mullah Krekar left for Norway in 2003, Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i was again the leader of Ansar al-Islam.<ref name=Presstv8-8-12>{{cite web|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=125357&sectionid=351020201 |title=No Operation |publisher=Presstv.ir |accessdate=2012-08-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930000329/http://www.presstv.ir/detail.aspx?id=125357&sectionid=351020201 |archivedate=September 30, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn May 4, 2010 Abu Abdullah al-Shafi'i was captured by US forces in Baghdad.<ref name=Presstv8-8-12 />\nOn December 15, 2011 Ansar al-Islam announced a new emir, Sheikh Abu Hashim al Ibrahim<ref name=lwjjan2012>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2012/01/ansar_al_islam_names.php |title=Ansar al Islam names new leader|website=Long War Journal|date=2012-01-05 |accessdate=2014-01-08}}</ref>\nA history of the group published on Twitter in November, 2015 by Abu al-Waleed al-Salafi states that \"a number of leaders of the group, including Abu Hashim Al Ibrahim, the amir of the group,\" were arrested \"at the beginning of 2014\"; the article does not at all suggest that any replacement emir had been appointed.<ref name=\"complete history\" />\n\n==Claimed and alleged attacks==\nAnsar al-Islam detonated a suicide car bomb on March 22, 2003, killing [[Australia]]n journalist [[Paul Moran (photojournalist)|Paul Moran]] and several others. The group was also thought to have been responsible for a September 9, 2003 attempted bombing of a [[United States Department of Defense]] office in [[Erbil]], which killed three people.\n\nOn February 1, 2004 suicide bombings hit parallel [[Eid al-Fitr|Eid]]-celebrations arranged by the two main Kurdish parties, PUK and [[Kurdistan Democratic Party of Iraq]] (KDP), in the Kurdish capital of [[Erbil]], killing 109 and wounding more than 200 partygoers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rudaw.net/english/kurdistan/01022019 |date=2019-02-01 |accessdate=2019-02-01 |title=PM Barzani stresses KDP-PUK unity 15 years after Erbil bombings |work=Rudaw}}</ref> Responsibility for this attack was claimed by the then unknown group [[Ansar al-Sunnah]], and stated to be in support of \"our brothers in Ansar al-Islam\".\n\nIn November 2008, an archbishop in [[Mosul]] received a threat signed by the \"Ansar al-Islam brigades\", warning all Christians to leave Iraq or else be killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pukmedia.com/english/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7622&Itemid=53 |title=\u0645\u06d5\u06a9\u062a\u06d5\u0628\u06cc \u0631\u0627\u06af\u06d5\u06cc\u0627\u0646\u062f\u0646\u06cc \u06cc\u06d5\u06a9\u06ce\u062a\u06cc\u06cc \u0646\u06cc\u0634\u062a\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u06cc \u06a9\u0648\u0631\u062f\u0633\u062a\u0627\u0646 |publisher=PUKmedia |accessdate=2012-08-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218201820/http://pukmedia.com/english/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=7622&Itemid=53 |archivedate=February 18, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nStabbing attack on police officer in Berlin on September 17, 2015 by Ansar operative [[Rafik Yousef]].<ref name=Huggler>{{cite news|last1=Huggler|first1=Justin|title=Islamic terrorist shot dead after Berlin attack on policewoman|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/11872727/Islamic-terrorist-shot-dead-after-Berlin-attack-on-policewoman.html |accessdate=17 September 2015|work=Telegraph|date=17 September 2015}}</ref><ref name=StabbingPolicewoman>{{cite news|title=Iraqi man shot dead in Berlin after stabbing policewoman |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/17/iraqi-man-shot-dead-in-berlin-after-stabbing-policewoman|accessdate=17 September 2015|agency=Agence France|work=The Guardian |date=17 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/germany/11872727/Islamic-terrorist-shot-dead-after-Berlin-attack-on-policewoman.html |title=Islamic terrorist shot dead after Berlin attack on policewoman|date=17 September 2015|work=Telegraph|accessdate=3 April 2016|last1=Huggler|first1=Justin}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books\n |1=Islamic terrorism\n |3=Islamic terrorist groups\n}}\n* [[Islamic Movement in Kurdistan]]\n* [[Kurdistan Islamic Union|Islamic Union of Kurdistan]]\n* [[Islamic Group Kurdistan|Islamic Group of Kurdistan]]\n* [[Islamic Kurdish League]]\n* [[Jamaat Ansar al-Sunna]]\n* [[Kurdish Revolutionary Hezbollah]]\n* [[Islamic Kurdistan Party|Partiya \u0130slamiya Kurdistan]]\n* [[(Turkish) Kurdish-Hizbullah]]\n* [[Islamic Kurdish Society]]\n* [[Islamic Fayli Grouping in Iraq]]\n* [[List of armed groups in the Iraqi Civil War]]\n* [[Al-Nusra Front]]\n* [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]\n* [[Rawti Shax]]\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/01402390902987046 Micah Zenko (2009) Foregoing Limited Force: The George W. Bush Administration's Decision Not to Attack Ansar Al-Islam, Journal of Strategic Studies, 32:4, 615-649]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.csmonitor.com/2003/1016/p12s01-woiq.htm The Rise and Fall of Ansar al-Islam], Christian Science Monitor\n* [http://www.cfr.org/publication/9237/ansar_alislam_iraq_islamistskurdish_separatists_.html Ansar al-Islam terrorist attacks]\n* [https://www.hrw.org/backgrounder/mena/ansarbk020503.htm Human Rights Watch: Ansar al-Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060224225910/http://www.crisisgroup.org/home/index.cfm?id=2104&l=1 Radical Islam in Iraqi Kurdistan: Ansar al-Islam]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/middle_east/2730253.stm Zarqawi and the 'al-Qaeda link'], February 5, 2003.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041110052354/http://www.aftenposten.no/english/local/article513564.ece Mullah Krekar arrested]( ), March 21, 2003.\n* [http://schanzer.pundicity.com/592/ansar-al-islam-postmortem-or-prelude-to-more Ansar al-Islam: Postmortem or Prelude to More Attacks?], April 3, 2003.\n* [http://www.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,426910,00.html Time.com article on first AI suicide attack], February 26, 2003\n* [http://schanzer.pundicity.com/582/ansar-al-islam-iraqs-al-qaeda-connection Ansar al-Islam: Iraq's al-Qaeda Connection], January 15, 2003\n* [https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2003/17823.htm State Department Designation of Ansar Al-Islam, February 20, 2003]\n* [https://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2004/30649.htm Foreign Terrorist Organizations: Designation of Ansar al-Islam (Al), Redesignation of Three Others (State Department), March 22, 2004]\n* [http://www.athenaintelligence.org/index2.html Athena Intelligence] Advanced Research Network on Insurgency and Terrorism\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090415022232/http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2002/03/25/020325fa_FACT1 The Great Terror], The New Yorker\n* [http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2003/02/10/030210fa_fact The Unknown: The C.I.A. and the Pentagon take another look at Al Qaeda and Iraq], The New Yorker\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041015080217/http://www.insightnewstv.com/d80/ Mullah Krekar Interview]\n\n{{Armed Iraqi Groups in the Iraq War and the Iraq Civil War}}\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n{{Militant Islamism}}\n\n[[Category:Iraqi insurgency (2003\u20132011)]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Japan]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Israel]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Canada]]\n[[Category:Organisations designated as terrorist by Australia]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist in Asia]]\n[[Category:Groups affiliated with al-Qaeda]]\n[[Category:Salafi groups]]\n[[Category:Anti-government factions of the Syrian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Factions in the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:2001 establishments in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Jihadist groups in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Jihadist groups in Syria]]\n[[Category:Paramilitary organizations based in Iraq]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Iraq]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing links to disambiguation pages, improving links, other minor cleanup tasks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ansar_al-Islam"}
{"title_page": "History of the Jews in Haiti", "text_new": "{{Jews and Judaism sidebar}}\n\nThe '''history of the Jews in Haiti''' stretches from the beginning of the European settlement until the modern day.\n\nAs of 2013, the Jewish population is around 25, predominately in the capital of [[Port-au-Prince]].<ref name=\"Jewish Virtual Library\">{{cite encyclopedia|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/vjw/haiti.html |title=Haiti |encyclopedia=[[Jewish Virtual Library]] |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===The first Jewish settlement===\nIn 1492, the first [[Jews|Jew]] to ever set foot in Haiti was [[Luis de Torres]],<ref name=\"JTA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/2004/02/13/archive/around-the-jewish-world-as-haiti-burns-its-few-jews-choose-business-over-politics |title=Around the Jewish World As Haiti Burns, Its Few Jews Choose Business over Politics |editor=Press |date=13 February 2004 |publisher=JTA (Jewish Telegraphic Agency) |accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref> an interpreter for [[Christopher Columbus]]. After Haiti was taken over and colonized by the French in 1633, many Dutch Jews (of whom many were [[Marrano]]) emigrated from [[Brazil]] in 1634 and became employees of the French sugar plantations and further developed the trade. In 1683, the Jews were expelled from Haiti and all other French colonies, due to the ''[[Code Noir]]'' (Black Code), which both restricted the activities of free Negroes and forbade the exercise of any religion other than [[Roman Catholic]]ism. However, despite the Code Noir, a limited number of Jews remained in French trading companies as leading officials, including foreign citizens ([[History of the Jews in the Netherlands|Dutch Jews]], [[History of the Jews in Denmark|Danish Jews]], and [[History of the Jews in England|English Jews]]) or holders of special residence permits (''lettres patentes''). These Jews tended to specialize in agricultural plantations, with [[Portuguese people|Portuguese Jews]] from [[Bordeaux]] and [[Bayonne]] settling mainly in the [[Tiburon Peninsula, Haiti|southern part]] of Haiti ([[Jacmel]], [[J\u00e9r\u00e9mie]], [[L\u00e9og\u00e2ne]], [[Les Cayes]], [[Petit-Go\u00e2ve]], and [[Port-au-Prince]]) and [[History of the Jews in Cura\u00e7ao|Cura\u00e7aoan Jews]] settling in the northern part ([[Cap-Haitien]] and [[Saint-Louis-du-Nord|Saint Louis]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0004_0_03964.html |title=Caribbeans, Spanish--Portuguese Nation of the: La Nacion |accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Arbell|first=Mordehay|title=The Jewish Nation of the Caribbean: The Spanish-Portuguese Jewish Settlements in the Caribbean and the Guianas|year=2002|publisher=Gefen Publishing House|isbn=965-229-279-6|pages=170, 292}}</ref>\n \nIn the mid-1700s, many Jews returned to Haiti, but were later murdered or expelled during the 1804 [[Haitian Revolution]] led by [[Toussaint Louverture]].\n\nDue to a lack of Jewish community centers, many youth did not grow up with a Jewish education and had to hide their Judaism, as only Catholics were permitted to attend public school. Jews generally preferred to settle on the coastline in port cities, as many were involved in commerce and trade, establishing communities in major industry centers. Recently, archaeologists uncovered an ancient synagogue of [[Crypto-Judaism|Crypto-Jews]] in the city of [[J\u00e9r\u00e9mie]], the only one found on the island; J\u00e9r\u00e9mie was inhabited by many [[Multiracial|mixed-race]] families of Jewish descent. Several Jewish tombstones have also been found in port cities such as [[Cap-Ha\u00eftien]] and [[Jacmel]].<ref name=\"JTA\"/><ref name=\"Virtual Jewish World\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/vjw/haiti.html|title=The Virtual Jewish World: Haiti|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref> By the end of the 19th century, approximately thirty mostly [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardi]] Jewish families had arrived from [[History of the Jews in Lebanon|Lebanon]], [[History of the Jews in Syria|Syria]], and [[History of the Jews in Lebanon|Egypt]]; many Jews from the Middle East felt secure emigrating to Haiti, as a law in France had been passed during this period that gave French citizenship to minorities in the Americas.\n\n==Modern Times==\n[[File:Haitian passport issued to Jewish holocaust survivor, stamped in Argentina July 1941.jpg|thumb|right|Passport issued to Hans Erich Max Emden by the Haitian government, who managed to escape the holocaust. In 1941 he used it to travel to Argentina.]]\nIn 1915, during the [[United States occupation of Haiti]], roughly 200 Jews lived in Haiti at the time. During the 20 years period of occupation, many Jews left Haiti for the United States and [[South America]].<ref name=\"Virtual Jewish World\"/> In 1937, Haiti was responsible for saving about 70 [[Jews|Jewish]] families (an estimated total of up to 300 lives) during the [[Holocaust]] (according to the [[American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee]]), by issuing passports and visas to Jews escaping [[Nazi]] persecution.<ref name=\"Virtual Jewish World\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdc.org/jdc-field-blog/2010/from-the-archives-haiti.html |title=From the Archives: Haiti Helped Holocaust Refugees |editor=Press |date=28 January 2010 |publisher=American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee |accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> Some were [[Austria]]n Jews, [[Poland|Polish]] Jews, [[Germany|German]] Jews, and a trickle of [[Romania]]n Jew and [[Czech Republic|Czech]] Jewish descent. Haiti played a small, yet critical role in saving Jewish lives during the darkest chapter in the Jewish story<ref name=\"Kreyollicious\">{{cite web|url=http://kreyolicious.com/haiti-history-101-haitis-role-in-saving-jewish-families-during-the-holocaust/3976/ |title=Haiti History 101: Haiti\u2019s Role in Saving Jewish Families During the Holocaust |author=KAT |accessdate=7 February 2014}}</ref> Unfortunately, though, it seems that more Jews were unable to acquire visas to Haiti due to the cost. Professor David Bankier, of the Institute of Contemporary Jewry at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, said that after 1938, ''\u201cthe cost [of a visa] was outrageous: If you wanted to go to Haiti, you had to pay $5,000.\u201d''<ref name=\"Virtual Jewish World\"/> Haiti at the time, was still unfairly paying reparations on an exorbitant debt with interest fees to France after the [[Haitian Revolution]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/08/16/france-asked-to-return-money-extorted-from-haiti/ |title=France Asked to Return Money \u2018Extorted\u2019 From Haiti |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=2014-02-12}}</ref> that could have hindered their efforts to continue issuing these visas for free. There were others apart from this bunch who never came to Haiti at all, but from Germany they were given Haitian passports by the Haitian government that allowed them to flee Germany and into other countries.<ref name=\"Kreyollicious\"/> Grateful to the Haitian government, many of these European Jews stayed in Haiti until the late 1950s in which many Haitian Jews left, so that their children could marry other Jews and not assimilate, while finding better economic opportunities. The 1957 Jewish population of Haiti was about 200.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Jewish Community of Haiti |url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/haiti |publisher=[[The Museum of the Jewish People at Beit Hatfutsot]] |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> The mid-20th century was a time where a continued departure of Jews from Haiti for the United States and Panama because of the economic conditions and civil violence in the country.<ref name=\"Jewish Virtual Library\"/>\n\n===Judaism===\nToday, the Jewish community is led by Rabbi Douglas Lapin, a local businessman.  The Jewish community is known as the \"Consistoire d'Haiti\" and has been recognized as the representative of the Jewish community by the Haitian Ministry of Religion (Ministere des Cultes) <Rep. d'Haiti; Ministere des Cultes DG/909 6 fevrier 2017>.  Rabbi Lapin has likewise been recognized as the Rabbi in Haiti by the Haitian government<Tribunal de Premiere Instance de Port-au-Prince; Recipisse No. 3710084007-7; 4 Octobre 2017>.  The community is very small and mostly consists of UN, NGO, and diplomatic personnel, although there are a small number of Haitian Jewish families.  The community does Kosher chicken slaughtering (shkita) and has occasional gatherings for Jewish festivals such as Succos and Purim.  There is also an Esrog, Myrtle (Hadasim) and Willow (Aravos) plantation to supply local needs for Succos.\nThe community is working on developing a synagogue and community center.  There is a complete library of Jewish liturgical books (seforim), Megillas Esther and Sefer Torah.\n\n===Business===\nThe 1960s was a time of wealth and high hopes of large future development for Haiti. At the time met many family Jewish names such as: Alvarez, Cardozo, Cohen, Dreyfus, Goldman, Hakim, Hillel, Khan, Monsanto, Pereira, Salzmann, Silveira, and Weiner, which most had forgotten their ethno-religious backgrounds. Today, less than a hundred Jews remain in Haiti on its 9.5 million inhabitants; however, the Weiners (coffee exporters) and the Salzmanns (refugees from Austria) are still today relevant in trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehaitianculture.blogspot.com/2013_05_01_archive.html |title=First Jews In Haiti |accessdate=2014-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.desinfos.com/spip.php?page=article&id_article=16680 |title=Ha\u00efti, les Juifs et Isra\u00ebl |editor=Yerouchalmi |date=17 January 2010 |publisher=Des Infos |accessdate=21 December 2015|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Haitian Jews==\n* David Ades \u2013 political writer for [[Le Nouvelliste (Haiti)|Le Nouvelliste]]\n* Daniel Kedar \u2013 businessman; co-founder of Prodev\n* Elisabeth Silvera \u2013 President of the Fondation Haiti Solidarite (FHS)\n* [[Eric Andr\u00e9]] \u2013 actor, comedian and television host\n* Gaston Michel \u2013 local tourism official\n* [[Gilbert Bigio]] \u2013 businessman billionaire of [[Syria]]n descent and Israeli honorary consul in Haiti\n* Kenneth Ades \u2013 financial service provider\n* [[Luis de Torres]] \u2013 one of the first Jews to settle on Haiti, and also [[Christopher Columbus]]'s interpreter\n* Monique Bigio \u2013 shareholder of [[PromoCapital]]\n* [[Monique P\u00e9an]] \u2013 fine [[jewelry designer]]\n* Reuven Bigio \u2013 founder of FAE (Fondation Appui \u00e0 l'Education)\n* Robin Padberg \u2013 CEO of telecommunications company [[Comcel Haiti|Voila]] in Haiti\n* Rudolph Dana \u2013 CEO of Transec SA\n* [[Sol (musician)|Sol]] \u2013 is a musician of [[Russia]]n descent\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Haiti}}\n* [[Haiti-Israel relations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Martinque, Guadeloupe, Haiti: M. Arbell, \"Jewish Settlements in the French Colonies in the Caribbean (Martinique, Guadeloupe, Haiti) and the 'Black Code,'\" in: Jews and the Expansion of Europe to the West (2001); A. Cahen, \"Les Juifs dans les colonies francaises au xviii siecle,\" in: Revue des Etudes Juives, 4 (1882): 127\u201345, 238\u201372.\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=T3t__sdb_SkC&pg=PA288 ''The Jewish Nation of the Caribbean'']. pp.&nbsp;288\u2013297.\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=m0JAGMuePO0C&pg=PA304 ''Jews and the Expansion of Europe to the West, 1400-1800'']. pp.&nbsp;304\u2013308.\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=BYiXSOTFvHIC&pg=PA131 ''Rara!: Vodou, Power, and Performance in Haiti and Its Diaspora, Volume 1'']. pp.&nbsp;131\u2013133.\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=cbxYAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA239 ''Encyclopaedia Judaica, Volume 9'']. pp.&nbsp;239\u2013240.\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Features/In-Thespotlight/A-look-into-Haitis-tiny-Jewish-community|title=A look into Haiti's tiny Jewish community|newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}}\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1147935.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328145836/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-1147935.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 March 2015|title=Antisemitism Without Jews; In Haiti, a Short Journey Into Myth, Memory and Nightmare|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}} {{paywall}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://forward.com/articles/123890/haiti-s-jewish-remnant-keeps-the-faith-and-lends/|title=Haiti\u2019s Jewish Remnant Keeps the Faith and Lends a Hand Amid the Crisis|date=20 January 2010|publisher=[[The Jewish Daily Forward]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/2010/04/23/life-religion/haitis-jews-try-to-pick-up-the-pieces|title=Haiti\u2019s Jews try to pick up the pieces|publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]|accessdate=19 October 2014}}\n* Bernard, Joseph jr, \"Histoire juive d'Haiti\". Port-au-Prince, Editions Henri Deschamps, 2012.\n\n==External links==\n*[https://wjc-org-website.s3.amazonaws.com/production/document/file/82/2bf54a971856d1302eda682eebe3a81e46ab6e93.pdf], (Haiti, Israel, and the Jews), [[World Jewish Congress]] by Mordechai Arbell\n*[http://www2.webster.edu/~corbetre/haiti/misctopic/ethnic/jewshistory2.htm], (Haiti's few Jews hold on to history)\n*[http://personal.stevens.edu/~llevine/Early%20Haitian%20Jewish%20History_v3.pdf], (Early Haitian Jewish History)\n*[http://www.reformjudaism.org/blog/2013/08/07/vodou-rock-and-cherry-manischewitz-reflections-jew-visiting-haiti], (Vodou Rock and Cherry Manischewitz: Reflections of a Jew Visiting Haiti)\n*[http://www.kosherdelight.com/Haiti.htm], (Jewish and Kosher Haiti)\n\n{{Haiti topics}}\n{{Haitian people}}\n{{North America in topic|History of the Jews in}}\n\n[[Category:Jews and Judaism in Haiti| ]]\n[[Category:Religion in Haiti]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Haiti]]\n[[Category:History of the Jews in the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:People of Saint-Domingue]]\n", "text_old": "{{Jews and Judaism sidebar}}\n\nThe '''history of the Jews in Haiti''' stretches from the beginning of the European settlement until the modern day.\n\nAs of 2013, the Jewish population is around 25, predominately in the capital of [[Port-au-Prince]].<ref name=\"Jewish Virtual Library\">{{cite encyclopedia|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/vjw/haiti.html |title=Haiti |encyclopedia=[[Jewish Virtual Library]] |accessdate=2014-02-07}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===The first Jewish settlement===\nIn 1492, the first [[Jews|Jew]] to ever set foot in Haiti was [[Luis de Torres]],<ref name=\"JTA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/2004/02/13/archive/around-the-jewish-world-as-haiti-burns-its-few-jews-choose-business-over-politics |title=Around the Jewish World As Haiti Burns, Its Few Jews Choose Business over Politics |editor=Press |date=13 February 2004 |publisher=JTA (Jewish Telegraphic Agency) |accessdate=21 December 2015}}</ref> an interpreter for [[Christopher Columbus]]. After Haiti was taken over and colonized by the French in 1633, many Dutch Jews (of whom many were [[Marrano]]) emigrated from [[Brazil]] in 1634 and became employees of the French sugar plantations and further developed the trade. In 1683, the Jews were expelled from Haiti and all other French colonies, due to the ''[[Code Noir]]'' (Black Code), which both restricted the activities of free Negroes and forbade the exercise of any religion other than [[Roman Catholic]]ism. However, despite the Code Noir, a limited number of Jews remained in French trading companies as leading officials, including foreign citizens ([[History of the Jews in the Netherlands|Dutch Jews]], [[History of the Jews in Denmark|Danish Jews]], and [[History of the Jews in England|English Jews]]) or holders of special residence permits (''lettres patentes''). These Jews tended to specialize in agricultural plantations, with [[Portuguese people|Portuguese Jews]] from [[Bordeaux]] and [[Bayonne]] settling mainly in the [[Tiburon Peninsula, Haiti|southern part]] of Haiti ([[Jacmel]], [[J\u00e9r\u00e9mie]], [[L\u00e9og\u00e2ne]], [[Les Cayes]], [[Petit-Go\u00e2ve]], and [[Port-au-Prince]]) and [[History of the Jews in Cura\u00e7ao|Cura\u00e7aoan Jews]] settling in the northern part ([[Cap-Haitien]] and [[Saint-Louis-du-Nord|Saint Louis]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/judaica/ejud_0002_0004_0_03964.html |title=Caribbeans, Spanish--Portuguese Nation of the: La Nacion |accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Arbell|first=Mordehay|title=The Jewish Nation of the Caribbean: The Spanish-Portuguese Jewish Settlements in the Caribbean and the Guianas|year=2002|publisher=Gefen Publishing House|isbn=965-229-279-6|pages=170, 292}}</ref>\n \nIn the mid-1700s, many Jews returned to Haiti, but were later murdered or expelled during the 1804 [[Haitian Revolution]] led by [[Toussaint Louverture]].\n\nDue to a lack of Jewish community centers, many youth did not grow up with a Jewish education and had to hide their Judaism, as only Catholics were permitted to attend public school. Jews generally preferred to settle on the coastline in port cities, as many were involved in commerce and trade, establishing communities in major industry centers. Recently, archaeologists uncovered an ancient synagogue of [[Crypto-Judaism|Crypto-Jews]] in the city of [[J\u00e9r\u00e9mie]], the only one found on the island; J\u00e9r\u00e9mie was inhabited by many [[Multiracial|mixed-race]] families of Jewish descent. Several Jewish tombstones have also been found in port cities such as [[Cap-Ha\u00eftien]] and [[Jacmel]].<ref name=\"JTA\"/><ref name=\"Virtual Jewish World\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/vjw/haiti.html|title=The Virtual Jewish World: Haiti|publisher=|accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref> By the end of the 19th century, approximately thirty mostly [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardi]] Jewish families had arrived from [[History of the Jews in Lebanon|Lebanon]], [[History of the Jews in Syria|Syria]], and [[History of the Jews in Lebanon|Egypt]]; many Jews from the Middle East felt secure emigrating to Haiti, as a law in France had been passed during this period that gave French citizenship to minorities in the Americas.\n\n==Modern Times==\n[[File:Haitian passport issued to Jewish holocaust survivor, stamped in Argentina July 1941.jpg|thumb|right|Passport issued to Hans Erich Max Emden by the Haitian government, who managed to escape the holocaust. In 1941 he used it to travel to Argentina.]]\nIn 1915, during the [[United States occupation of Haiti]], roughly 200 Jews lived in Haiti at the time. During the 20 years period of occupation, many Jews left Haiti for the United States and [[South America]].<ref name=\"Virtual Jewish World\"/> In 1937, Haiti was responsible for saving about 70 [[Jews|Jewish]] families (an estimated total of up to 300 lives) during the [[Holocaust]] (according to the [[American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee]]), by issuing passports and visas to Jews escaping [[Nazi]] persecution.<ref name=\"Virtual Jewish World\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jdc.org/jdc-field-blog/2010/from-the-archives-haiti.html |title=From the Archives: Haiti Helped Holocaust Refugees |editor=Press |date=28 January 2010 |publisher=American Jewish Joint Distribution Committee |accessdate=19 February 2016}}</ref> Some were [[Austria]]n Jews, [[Poland|Polish]] Jews, [[Germany|German]] Jews, and a trickle of [[Romania]]n Jew and [[Czech Republic|Czech]] Jewish descent. Haiti played a small, yet critical role in saving Jewish lives during the darkest chapter in the Jewish story<ref name=\"Kreyollicious\">{{cite web|url=http://kreyolicious.com/haiti-history-101-haitis-role-in-saving-jewish-families-during-the-holocaust/3976/ |title=Haiti History 101: Haiti\u2019s Role in Saving Jewish Families During the Holocaust |author=KAT |accessdate=7 February 2014}}</ref> Unfortunately, though, it seems that more Jews were unable to acquire visas to Haiti due to the cost. Professor David Bankier, of the Institute of Contemporary Jewry at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, said that after 1938, ''\u201cthe cost [of a visa] was outrageous: If you wanted to go to Haiti, you had to pay $5,000.\u201d''<ref name=\"Virtual Jewish World\"/> Haiti at the time, was still unfairly paying reparations on an exorbitant debt with interest fees to France after the [[Haitian Revolution]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thelede.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/08/16/france-asked-to-return-money-extorted-from-haiti/ |title=France Asked to Return Money \u2018Extorted\u2019 From Haiti |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=2014-02-12}}</ref> that could have hindered their efforts to continue issuing these visas for free. There were others apart from this bunch who never came to Haiti at all, but from Germany they were given Haitian passports by the Haitian government that allowed them to flee Germany and into other countries.<ref name=\"Kreyollicious\"/> Grateful to the Haitian government, many of these European Jews stayed in Haiti until the late 1950s in which many Haitian Jews left, so that their children could marry other Jews and not assimilate, while finding better economic opportunities. The 1957 Jewish population of Haiti was about 200.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Jewish Community of Haiti |url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/haiti |publisher=[[The Museum of the Jewish People at Beit Hatfutsot]] |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> The mid-20th century was a time where a continued departure of Jews from Haiti for the United States and Panama because of the economic conditions and civil violence in the country.<ref name=\"Jewish Virtual Library\"/>\n\n===Judaism===\nToday, the Jewish community is led by Rabbi Douglas Lapin, a local businessman.  The Jewish community is known as the \"Consistoire d'Haiti\" and has been recognized as the representative of the Jewish community by the Haitian Ministry of Religion (Ministere des Cultes) <Rep. d'Haiti; Ministere des Cultes DG/909 6 fevrier 2017>.  Rabbi Lapin has likewise been recognized as the Rabbi in Haiti by the Haitian government<Tribunal de Premiere Instance de Port au Prince; Recipisse No. 3710084007-7; 4 Octobre 2017>.  The community is very small and mostly consists of UN, NGO, and diplomatic personnel, although there are a small number of Haitian Jewish families.  The community does Kosher chicken slaughtering (shkita) and has occasional gatherings for Jewish festivals such as Succos and Purim.  There is also an Esrog, Myrtle (Hadasim) and Willow (Aravos) plantation to supply local needs for Succos.\nThe community is working on developing a synagogue and community center.  There is a complete library of Jewish liturgical books (seforim), Megillas Esther and Sefer Torah.\n\n===Business===\nThe 1960s was a time of wealth and high hopes of large future development for Haiti. At the time met many family Jewish names such as: Alvarez, Cardozo, Cohen, Dreyfus, Goldman, Hakim, Hillel, Khan, Monsanto, Pereira, Salzmann, Silveira, and Weiner, which most had forgotten their ethno-religious backgrounds. Today, less than a hundred Jews remain in Haiti on its 9.5 million inhabitants; however, the Weiners (coffee exporters) and the Salzmanns (refugees from Austria) are still today relevant in trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehaitianculture.blogspot.com/2013_05_01_archive.html |title=First Jews In Haiti |accessdate=2014-02-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.desinfos.com/spip.php?page=article&id_article=16680 |title=Ha\u00efti, les Juifs et Isra\u00ebl |editor=Yerouchalmi |date=17 January 2010 |publisher=Des Infos |accessdate=21 December 2015|language=fr}}</ref>\n\n==Notable Haitian Jews==\n* David Ades \u2013 political writer for [[Le Nouvelliste (Haiti)|Le Nouvelliste]]\n* Daniel Kedar \u2013 businessman; co-founder of Prodev\n* Elisabeth Silvera \u2013 President of the Fondation Haiti Solidarite (FHS)\n* [[Eric Andr\u00e9]] \u2013 actor, comedian and television host\n* Gaston Michel \u2013 local tourism official\n* [[Gilbert Bigio]] \u2013 businessman billionaire of [[Syria]]n descent and Israeli honorary consul in Haiti\n* Kenneth Ades \u2013 financial service provider\n* [[Luis de Torres]] \u2013 one of the first Jews to settle on Haiti, and also [[Christopher Columbus]]'s interpreter\n* Monique Bigio \u2013 shareholder of [[PromoCapital]]\n* [[Monique P\u00e9an]] \u2013 fine [[jewelry designer]]\n* Reuven Bigio \u2013 founder of FAE (Fondation Appui \u00e0 l'Education)\n* Robin Padberg \u2013 CEO of telecommunications company [[Comcel Haiti|Voila]] in Haiti\n* Rudolph Dana \u2013 CEO of Transec SA\n* [[Sol (musician)|Sol]] \u2013 is a musician of [[Russia]]n descent\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Haiti}}\n* [[Haiti-Israel relations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Martinque, Guadeloupe, Haiti: M. Arbell, \"Jewish Settlements in the French Colonies in the Caribbean (Martinique, Guadeloupe, Haiti) and the 'Black Code,'\" in: Jews and the Expansion of Europe to the West (2001); A. Cahen, \"Les Juifs dans les colonies francaises au xviii siecle,\" in: Revue des Etudes Juives, 4 (1882): 127\u201345, 238\u201372.\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=T3t__sdb_SkC&pg=PA288 ''The Jewish Nation of the Caribbean'']. pp.&nbsp;288\u2013297.\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=m0JAGMuePO0C&pg=PA304 ''Jews and the Expansion of Europe to the West, 1400-1800'']. pp.&nbsp;304\u2013308.\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=BYiXSOTFvHIC&pg=PA131 ''Rara!: Vodou, Power, and Performance in Haiti and Its Diaspora, Volume 1'']. pp.&nbsp;131\u2013133.\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=cbxYAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA239 ''Encyclopaedia Judaica, Volume 9'']. pp.&nbsp;239\u2013240.\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Features/In-Thespotlight/A-look-into-Haitis-tiny-Jewish-community|title=A look into Haiti's tiny Jewish community|newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post